# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: apple-cider
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] The **6abc Dunkin' Thanksgiving Day Parade** is an annual Thanksgiving Day parade held in Philadelphia, Pennsylvania.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] It is currently sponsored and broadcast by ABC owned-and-operated television station WPVI-TV, through a co-sponsorship agreement with restaurant chain Dunkin'.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] It is currently the oldest Thanksgiving parade in the United States, having been held through the Great Depression and World War II, and was created by Gimbels department store in 1920.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Gimbels sponsored the parade until the store's bankruptcy and closure in 1986.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] The annual Philadelphia Thanksgiving Day Parade began in 1920.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] It is the longest continuously held Thanksgiving day parade in the country.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Like other parades of its type, it features balloons, floats, high school marching bands, and celebrities.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Gimbels department store sponsored the 1920 parade as the Gimbels Thanksgiving Day Parade; it continued annually despite World War II.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Ellis Gimbel, one of the founders of Gimbels Department Stores, wanted his toy land to be the destination of holiday shoppers everywhere.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] He had more than 50 store employees dressed in costume and sent to walk in their first Thanksgiving Day parade.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] The parade featured floats as marchers paraded down Market Street, with the parade's finale featuring Santa Claus arriving at the eighth-floor toy department at Gimbels, where he climbed the ladder of a Philadelphia Fire Department ladder truck.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Gimbels emulated other holiday parades already in existence.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] The Santa Claus Parade in Peoria, Illinois, is held on the day after Thanksgiving and is the oldest, continuously held holiday parade in the country since 1887, under the sponsorship of Frederick Block and the Schipper & Block, later renamed Block & Kuhl Department Store.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Block's example led to the founding of similar parades in other cities.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] When Batus Inc., which then owned Gimbels, was unable to find a buyer for the store in 1986, the Gimbels' chain was liquidated, leaving the fate of the country's oldest parade uncertain.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Boscov's, a family-owned department store based in Reading, Pennsylvania, and WPVI (also known as 6abc), the ABC owned and operated station in Philadelphia, replaced Gimbels as sponsorships of the parade.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] They renamed the event as the 6abc Boscov's Thanksgiving Day Parade.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] In 2004, the parade celebrated its 85th anniversary with new balloons and floats.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] An opening number paid tribute to the celebrities who had participated during its history.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] In 2005, it featured the most celebrities in history, as well as eight new balloons, also the most in its history.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] In 2007, the parade presented the first parade float with a built-in ice rink.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Disney's *High School Musical: The Ice Tour* utilized the rink.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] In August 2008, Boscov's Department Stores filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection and planned to close several stores, due to financial problems from the widespread recession.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] They withdrew their sponsorship of the parade.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Swedish furniture manufacturer IKEA, which has a store and its North American home office in nearby Conshohocken, Pennsylvania, replaced Boscov's as parade co-sponsor from that year until 2010.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] In June 2011, Dunkin' Donuts announced that they would sponsor the parade.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] In addition to balloons and marching bands, the show features ABC stars, actors from stage and screen, Disney characters, and local personalities, including members of the Action News team.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] In 2020, due to the COVID-19 pandemic, the parade was held as a television-only event.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] The *6abc Dunkin' Thanksgiving Celebration* featured modifications similar to those made by the Macy's and America's Thanksgiving Parades.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] The parade returned to its traditional format in 2021.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Since 1966, the parade has been broadcast on WPVI, as well as simulcast on other television stations throughout the United States.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Viewers could also watch the telecast on the station's website, 6abc.com, ABC News Live, Disney+ and Hulu, and since 2023, the parade has been aired internationally via the YouTube page of ABC News.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Jim O'Brien was the program's first host; Dave Roberts became a perennial host upon joining the station in 1978.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] After the sudden death of O'Brien in 1983, WPVI's Lisa Thomas-Laury joined as Roberts's co-host.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Together, Roberts and Thomas-Laury hosted the parade for nearly 20 years.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] When Thomas-Laury began to experience health problems in 2002, WPVI weather anchor Cecily Tynan replaced her.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] 2006 marked the program's first high-definition telecast.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Since her return to WPVI, Thomas-Laury helped host the finale in 2006 and 2007.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] In 2009, the station announced that Roberts would retire from broadcasting on December 11 of that year.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Thomas-Laury made a special appearance in 2009, to celebrate Roberts's years as host.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Thomas-Laury (who would subsequently retire from broadcasting in 2016) and Roberts both made a special appearance in the broadcast booth during the centennial edition of the parade in 2019.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] The current hosting team is Tynan and WPVI news anchor Rick Williams, who replaced Roberts.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Since 2024, the parade has simulcastly streamed nationally on ABC News Live, Disney+, and Hulu.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] WPVI also broadcasts annual live coverage of Philadelphia's Pulaski, Columbus, and Puerto Rican parades.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Balloons have been created to represent a wide variety of characters from popular children's books, including folk tales, toys, comic books, animated movies and cartoons, television series (such as *Sesame Street*), films and other genres.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Increasingly over the years, the balloons have featured characters who have tie-in marketing of toys, games, and accessories.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] In addition to the well-known balloons and floats, the parade also features live music and other performances.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] High-school marching bands from across the country participate, and the television broadcasts feature performances by famous singers and bands as well as appearances by local celebrities and actors from ABC shows.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Since 1997, the parade has also featured a tap routine called "FanTAPulous," with more than 450 dancers from the East Coast.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Other special guests include state and national beauty contest winners, cheerleaders of major sports teams, casts from musicals performing in Philadelphia, and Santa and Mrs.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] In 2024, the Philadelphia Ghostbusters joined the parade line up for the first time.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] They were accompanied by members of the Delco Ghostbusters, Ghostbusters of New Jersey, and Diamond State Ghostbusters.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] For more than 25 years, WPVI-TV has partnered with the Boy Scouts of America Cradle of Liberty Council in their *Scouting For Food* program to collectively coordinate one of the most massive food drives in the nation.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Until 2006, it was called the *6abc/Boy Scouts Holiday Food Drive*.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] In 2006, the Holiday Food Drive amassed 120,000 lbs of food, and for 2010 Boy Scouts troops' efforts led to the collection of over 40,000 pounds of food towards the cumulative total.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] The food drive distributes paper bags to residents' homes and collection boxes at local stores in the region.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] A few weeks later, they are sent to help those in need at Thanksgiving and the end of year holidays.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] The Boy Scouts also go to the parade route every year and collect food from spectators.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] The parade and food drive sponsors are generally the same.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] In June 2011, Dunkin' Donuts announced that they would also co-sponsor the food drive.
[src:apple-cider/6abc-dunkin-thanksgiving-day-parade] Proceeds of the food drive currently benefit Philabundance.
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] Lucy encourages Charlie Brown to try and kick her football to honor the tradition of Thanksgiving football, then as usual pulls the ball away just before Charlie Brown reaches it and tells him that some traditions fade away.
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] Charlie Brown, Snoopy, Woodstock and Linus then prepare a feast of toast, pan-fried popcorn, pretzel sticks, jelly beans and sundaes.
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] Once the friends arrive, Linus says a grace based on the First Thanksgiving and Snoopy deals the plates like a casino dealer.
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] An enraged Peppermint Patty rejects the meal for not including traditional foods.
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] Marcie reminds Peppermint Patty that she invited herself to the meal.
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] Peppermint Patty humbly asks Marcie to apologize to Charlie Brown on her behalf (unintentionally paralleling *The Courtship of Miles Standish*).
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] Marcie reluctantly agrees, but Peppermint Patty soon follows and apologizes directly.
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] Charlie Brown calls his grandmother to explain why his family is late to dinner; she invites all his friends to join them.
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] On the drive over, they sing "Over the River and Through the Wood"; Charlie Brown remarks the one thing wrong with a song about "grandmother's house:" his lives in a condominium.
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] Back at Snoopy's doghouse, he and Woodstock partake in a traditional meal among themselves.
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] This is the last TV special that uses the same cast from *Snoopy Come Home*, *You're Not Elected, Charlie Brown*, and *There's No Time for Love, Charlie Brown*.
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] In the next television special, Kohn, DeFaria, and Momberger would be succeeded in their respective roles by Melanie Kohn (Robin's younger sister), Donna Forman, and Lynn Mortensen, respectively.
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] The special first aired on CBS on Tuesday, November 20, 1973, two days before Thanksgiving.
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] It placed third in the Nielsen ratings for the week, behind *All in the Family* and *Sanford & Son*.
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] The special continued to air every year on CBS (skipping 1982, 1983, and 1988) through Nov.
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] The Disney Channel and Nickelodeon returned the special for re-airing in the 1990s (in the latter channel's case, under the "You're on Nickelodeon, Charlie Brown" umbrella of productions) and then, in 2001, it moved, along with the rest of the *Peanuts* specials, to ABC.
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] In contrast to CBS, ABC aired the special every year through 2019, on several days in the week leading up to Thanksgiving, and it regularly won its time slot.
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] As the special runs slightly over a half-hour with commercials, ABC typically filled the remaining portion of the full hour with other *Peanuts* programming.
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] From 2008 to 2019, the remaining time was filled by a slightly abridged edit of "The Mayflower Voyagers," the premiere episode of the 1988 miniseries *This Is America, Charlie Brown*.
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] Starting in 2020, the special (along with the rest of the *Peanuts* library) has exclusively aired on Apple TV+; under the terms of the agreement, Apple TV+ must provide a three-day window in November in which the special is available for free.
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] On November 18, 2020, Apple announced they had reached an agreement to air the special on Sunday, November 22, 2020, the Sunday before Thanksgiving, commercial free on PBS and PBS Kids.
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] Apple renewed its exclusive streaming rights to the special in an agreement announced October 2, 2025, the 75th anniversary of the first published *Peanuts* comic strip.
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] The special is also broadcast in Canada, usually in early October in line with the Canadian observance of Thanksgiving.
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] The special is aired on Family Channel as of 2018, with the special aired on the day before Thanksgiving and on Thanksgiving Day, which takes place on the second Monday of October in Canada.
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] The music for *A Charlie Brown Thanksgiving* was composed by Vince Guaraldi and conducted/arranged by John Scott Trotter.
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] The score was recorded by the Vince Guaraldi Quintet on August 20, 22, September 4, and October 1 1973, at Wally Heider Studios, featuring Tom Harrell (trumpet), Chuck Bennett (trombone), Seward McCain (electric bass), and Mike Clark (drums).
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] On October 20, 2023, the complete original remastered recordings were officially released by Lee Mendelson Film Productions in honor of the special's 50th anniversary, presenting the full score and several previously unreleased tracks for the first time.
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] The special was released on RCA's SelectaVision CED format in 1982 as part of the *A Charlie Brown Festival Vol.
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] It was released on VHS by Kartes Video Communications (later KVC Home Video) in 1987.
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] It was released by Paramount Home Video on VHS on September 28, 1994 and was re-released in clamshell packaging on October 1, 1996.
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] *A Charlie Brown Thanksgiving* was released on DVD by Paramount Home Entertainment on September 12, 2000.
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] It was re-released by Warner Home Video in remastered form on October 7, 2008.
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] It was released on a Blu-ray/DVD Combo Pack by Warner Home Video on October 5, 2010.
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] The special was released in a 40th anniversary deluxe edition DVD by Warner Home Video with the same features from previous editions on October 1, 2013.
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] The deluxe edition DVD also features "The *Mayflower* Voyagers".
[src:apple-cider/a-charlie-brown-thanksgiving] The special was released on Ultra HD Blu-ray on October 24, 2017.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Dickens wrote *A Christmas Carol* during a period when the British were exploring and re-evaluating past Christmas traditions, including carols, and newer customs such as cards and Christmas trees.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] He was influenced by the experiences of his own youth and by the Christmas stories of other authors, including Washington Irving and Douglas Jerrold.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Dickens had written three Christmas stories prior to the novella, and was inspired following a visit to the Field Lane Ragged School, one of several establishments for London's street children.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The treatment of the poor and the ability of a selfish man to redeem himself by transforming into a more sympathetic character are the key themes of the story.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] There is discussion among academics as to whether this is a fully secular story or a Christian allegory.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Published on 19 December, the first edition sold out by Christmas Eve; by the end of 1844 thirteen editions had been released.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Most critics reviewed the novella favourably.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The story was illicitly copied in January 1844; Dickens took legal action against the publishers, who went bankrupt, further reducing Dickens's small profits from the publication.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] He subsequently wrote four other Christmas stories.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] In 1849 he began public readings of the story, which proved so successful he undertook 127 further performances until 1870, the year of his death.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] *A Christmas Carol* has never been out of print and has been translated into several languages; the story has been adapted many times for film, stage, opera and other media.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] That night Scrooge is visited at home by Marley's ghost, who wanders the Earth entwined by heavy chains and money boxes forged during a lifetime of greed and selfishness.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Marley tells Scrooge that he has a single chance to avoid the same fate: he will be visited by three spirits and must listen or be cursed to carry much heavier chains of his own.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The first spirit, the Ghost of Christmas Past, takes Scrooge to Christmas scenes of Scrooge's boyhood, reminding him of a time when he was more innocent.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The scenes reveal Scrooge's lonely childhood at boarding school, his relationship with his beloved sister Fan, the long-dead mother of Fred, and a Christmas party hosted by his first employer, Mr Fezziwig, who treated him like a son.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Scrooge's neglected fiancée Belle is shown ending their relationship, as she realises that he will never love her as much as he loves money.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Finally, they visit a now-married Belle with her large, happy family on the Christmas Eve that Marley died.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Scrooge, upset by hearing a description of the man that he has become, demands that the ghost remove him from the house.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The second spirit, the Ghost of Christmas Present, takes Scrooge to a joyous market where people are buying the makings of Christmas dinner and to celebrations of Christmas in a miner's cottage and in a lighthouse.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Scrooge and the ghost also visit Fred's Christmas party.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] A major part of this stave is taken up with Bob Cratchit's family feast and introduces his youngest son, Tiny Tim, a happy boy who is seriously ill.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The spirit informs Scrooge that Tiny Tim will die unless the course of events changes.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Before disappearing, the spirit shows Scrooge two hideous, emaciated children named Ignorance and Want.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] He tells Scrooge to beware the former above all and mocks Scrooge's concern for their welfare.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The third spirit, the Ghost of Christmas Yet to Come, shows Scrooge a Christmas Day in the future.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The silent ghost reveals scenes involving the death of a disliked man whose funeral is attended by local businessmen only on condition that lunch is provided.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] His charwoman, laundress and the local undertaker steal his possessions to sell to a fence.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] When he asks the spirit to show a single person who feels emotion over his death, he is only given the pleasure of a poor couple who rejoice that his death gives them more time to put their finances in order.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] When Scrooge asks to see tenderness connected with any death, the ghost shows him Bob Cratchit and his family mourning the death of Tiny Tim.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The ghost then allows Scrooge to see a neglected grave, with a tombstone bearing Scrooge's name.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Sobbing, Scrooge pledges to change his ways.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Scrooge awakens on Christmas morning a changed man.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] He makes a large donation to the charity he rejected the previous day, anonymously sends a large turkey to the Cratchit home for Christmas dinner and spends the afternoon at Fred's Christmas party.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The following day he gives Cratchit an increase in pay, and begins to become a father figure to Tiny Tim.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] From then on Scrooge treats everyone with kindness, generosity and compassion, embodying the spirit of Christmas.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The writer Charles Dickens was born to a middle-class family which got into financial difficulties as a result of the spendthrift nature of his father John.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] In 1824 John was committed to the Marshalsea, a debtors' prison in Southwark, London.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Dickens, aged 12, was forced to pawn his collection of books, leave school and work at a dirty and rat-infested shoe-blacking factory.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The change in circumstances gave him what his biographer, Michael Slater, describes as a "deep personal and social outrage", which heavily influenced his writing and outlook.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] By the end of 1842 Dickens was a well-established author with six major works as well as several short stories, novellas and other pieces.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] On 31 December that year he began publishing his novel *Martin Chuzzlewit* as a monthly serial; it was his favourite work, but sales were disappointing and he faced temporary financial difficulties.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Celebrating the Christmas season had been growing in popularity through the Victorian era.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The Christmas tree was introduced in Britain during the 18th century, and its use was popularised by Queen Victoria and Prince Albert.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] In the early 19th century there had been a revival of interest in Christmas carols, following a decline in popularity over the previous hundred years.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The publication of Davies Gilbert's 1823 work *Some Ancient Christmas Carols, With the Tunes to Which They Were Formerly Sung in the West of England* and William Sandys's 1833 collection *Christmas Carols, Ancient and Modern* led to a growth in the form's popularity in Britain.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Dickens had an interest in Christmas, and his first story on the subject was "Christmas Festivities", published in *Bell's Weekly Messenger* in 1835; the story was then published as "A Christmas Dinner" in *Sketches by Boz* (1836).
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] "The Story of the Goblins Who Stole a Sexton", another Christmas story, appeared in the 1836 novel *The Pickwick Papers*.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] In the episode, a Mr Wardle describes a misanthropic sexton, Gabriel Grub, who undergoes a Christmas conversion after being visited by goblins who show him the past and future.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Slater considers that "the main elements of the *Carol* are present in the story", but not yet in a firm form.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The story is followed by a passage about Christmas in Dickens's editorial *Master Humphrey's Clock*.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The professor of English literature Paul Davis writes that although the "Goblins" story appears to be a prototype of *A Christmas Carol*, all Dickens's earlier writings about Christmas influenced the story.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Dickens was not the first author to celebrate the Christmas season in literature.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Among earlier authors who influenced Dickens was Washington Irving, whose 1819–20 work *The Sketch Book of Geoffrey Crayon, Gent.* included four essays on old English Christmas traditions that he experienced while staying at Aston Hall near Birmingham.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The tales and essays attracted Dickens, and the two authors shared the belief that returning to Christmas traditions might promote a type of social connection that they felt had been lost in the modern world.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Several works had an influence on the writing of *A Christmas Carol*, including two essays by his friend Douglas Jerrold: one from an 1841 issue of *Punch*, "How Mr.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Chokepear Keeps a Merry Christmas" and one from 1843, "The Beauties of the Police".
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] More broadly, Dickens was influenced by fairy tales and nursery stories, which he closely associated with Christmas, because he saw them as stories of conversion and transformation.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Dickens was touched by the lot of poor children in the middle decades of the 19th century.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] In early 1843 he toured the Cornish tin mines, where he was angered by seeing children working in appalling conditions.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The suffering he witnessed there was reinforced by a visit to the Field Lane Ragged School, one of several London schools set up for the education of the capital's half-starved, illiterate street children.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] In February 1843 the *Second Report of the Children's Employment Commission* was published.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] It was a parliamentary report exposing the effects of the Industrial Revolution upon working class children.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Horrified by what he read, Dickens planned to publish an inexpensive political pamphlet tentatively titled, *An Appeal to the People of England, on behalf of the Poor Man's Child*, but changed his mind, deferring the pamphlet's production until the end of the year.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] By mid-1843 Dickens was suffering from financial problems.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Sales of *Martin Chuzzlewit* were falling off, and his wife, Catherine, was pregnant with their fifth child.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Matters worsened when Chapman & Hall, his publishers, threatened to reduce his monthly income by £50 if sales dropped further.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] He began *A Christmas Carol* in October 1843.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Michael Slater, Dickens's biographer, describes the book as being "written at white heat"; it was completed in six weeks, the final pages being written in early December.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] He built much of the work in his head while taking night-time walks of 15 to 20 miles (24 to 32 km) around London.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Dickens's sister-in-law wrote how he "wept, and laughed, and wept again, and excited himself in a most extraordinary manner, in composition".
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] George Cruikshank, the illustrator who had earlier worked with Dickens on *Sketches by Boz* (1836) and *Oliver Twist* (1838), introduced him to the caricaturist John Leech.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] By 24 October Dickens invited Leech to work on *A Christmas Carol*, and four hand-coloured etchings and four black-and-white wood engravings by the artist accompanied the text.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Dickens's hand-written manuscript of the story does not include the sentence in the penultimate paragraph "... and to Tiny Tim, who did *not* die"; this was added later, during the printing process.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] This psychological conflict may be responsible for the two radically different Scrooges in the tale—one a cold, stingy and greedy semi-recluse, the other a benevolent, sociable man.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Scrooge could also be based on two misers: the eccentric John Elwes, MP, or Jemmy Wood, the owner of the Gloucester Old Bank and also known as "The Gloucester Miser".
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Elwell, Scrooge's views on the poor are a reflection of those of the demographer and political economist Thomas Malthus, while the miser's questions "Are there no prisons? ...
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] There are literary precursors for Scrooge in Dickens's own works.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Douglas-Fairhurst sees that the minor character Gabriel Grub from *The Pickwick Papers* was also an influence when creating Scrooge.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] It is possible that Scrooge's name came from a tombstone Dickens had seen on a visit to Edinburgh.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The grave was for Ebenezer Lennox Scroggie, whose job was given as a meal man—a corn merchant; Dickens misread the inscription as "mean man".
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] This theory has been described as "a probable Dickens hoax" for which "[n]o one could find any corroborating evidence".
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] When Dickens was young he lived near a tradesman's premises with the sign "Goodge and Marney", which may have provided the name for Scrooge's former business partner.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] For the chained Marley, Dickens drew on his memory of a visit to the Western Penitentiary in Pittsburgh, Pennsylvania, in March 1842, where he saw—and was affected by seeing—fettered prisoners.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] For the character Tiny Tim, Dickens used his nephew Henry, a disabled boy who was five at the time *A Christmas Carol* was written.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The two figures of Want and Ignorance, sheltering in the robes of the Ghost of Christmas Present, were inspired by the children Dickens had seen on his visit to a ragged school in the East End of London.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The transformation of Scrooge is central to the story.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Some writers, including the Dickens scholar Grace Moore, consider that there is a Christian theme running through *A Christmas Carol*, and that the novella should be seen as an allegory of the Christian concept of redemption.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Dickens's biographer Claire Tomalin sees the conversion of Scrooge as carrying the Christian message that "even the worst of sinners may repent and become a good man".
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Dickens's attitudes towards organised religion were complex; he based his beliefs and principles on the New Testament.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] His statement that Marley "had no bowels" is a reference to the "bowels of compassion" mentioned in the First Epistle of John, the reason for his eternal damnation.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Other writers, including Kelly, consider that Dickens put forward a "secular vision of this sacred holiday".
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] From a secular viewpoint, the cultural historian Penne Restad suggests that Scrooge's redemption underscores "the conservative, individualistic and patriarchal aspects" of Dickens's "*Carol* philosophy" of charity and altruism.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Dickens wrote *A Christmas Carol* in response to British social attitudes towards poverty, particularly child poverty, and wished to use the novella as a means to put forward his arguments against it.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The story shows Scrooge as a paradigm for self-interest, and the possible repercussions of ignoring the poor, especially children—personified by the allegorical figures of Want and Ignorance.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The two figures were created to arouse sympathy with readers—as was Tiny Tim.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Douglas-Fairhurst observes that the use of such figures allowed Dickens to present his message of the need for charity without alienating his largely middle-class readership.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] As the result of the disagreements with Chapman and Hall over the commercial failures of *Martin Chuzzlewit*, Dickens arranged to pay for the publishing himself, in exchange for a percentage of the profits.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Production of *A Christmas Carol* was not without problems.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The first printing was meant to have festive green endpapers, but they came out a dull olive colour.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Dickens's publisher Chapman and Hall replaced these with yellow endpapers and reworked the title page in harmonising red and blue shades.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The final product was bound in red cloth with gilt-edged pages, completed only two days before the publication date of 19 December 1843.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Following publication, Dickens arranged for the manuscript to be bound in red Morocco leather and presented as a gift to his solicitor, Thomas Mitton.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Priced at five shillings (equivalent to £27 in 2025), the first run of 6,000 copies sold out by Christmas Eve.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Chapman and Hall issued second and third editions before the new year, and the book continued to sell well into 1844.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] By the end of 1844 eleven more editions had been released.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Since its initial publication the book has been issued in numerous hardback and paperback editions, translated into several languages and has never been out of print.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] It was Dickens's most popular book in the United States, and sold over two million copies in the hundred years following its first publication there.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The high production costs upon which Dickens insisted led to reduced profits, and the first edition brought him only £230 (equivalent to £25,000 in 2025) rather than the £1,000 (equivalent to £110,000 in 2025) he expected.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] A year later, the profits were only £744, and Dickens was deeply disappointed.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] According to Douglas-Fairhurst, contemporary reviews of *A Christmas Carol* "were almost uniformly kind".
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] *The Illustrated London News* described how the story's "impressive eloquence ... its unfeigned lightness of heart—its playful and sparkling humour ... its gentle spirit of humanity" all put the reader "in good humour with ourselves, with each other, with the season and with the author".
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] After Dickens's death, Margaret Oliphant deplored the turkey and plum pudding aspects of the book but admitted that in the days of its first publication it was regarded as "a new gospel", and noted that the book was unique in that it made people behave better.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The religious press generally ignored the tale but, in January 1844, *Christian Remembrancer* thought the tale's old and hackneyed subject was treated in an original way and praised the author's sense of humour and pathos.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The writer and social thinker John Ruskin told a friend that he thought Dickens had taken the religion from Christmas, and had imagined it as "mistletoe and pudding—neither resurrection from the dead, nor rising of new stars, nor teaching of wise men, nor shepherds".
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] *The New Monthly Magazine* praised the story, but thought the book's physical excesses—the gilt edges and expensive binding—kept the price high, making it unavailable to the poor.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The review recommended that the tale should be printed on cheap paper and priced accordingly.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] An unnamed writer for *The Westminster Review* mocked Dickens's grasp of economics, asking "Who went without turkey and punch in order that Bob Cratchit might get them—for, unless there were turkeys and punch in surplus, someone must go without".
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Dickens had criticised the US in *American Notes* and *Martin Chuzzlewit*, making American readers reluctant to embrace his work, but by the end of the American Civil War, the book had gained wide recognition in American households.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] In 1863 *The New York Times* published an enthusiastic review, noting that the author brought the "old Christmas ... of bygone centuries and remote manor houses, into the living rooms of the poor of today".
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] In January 1844 Parley's Illuminated Library published an unauthorised version of the story in a condensed form which they sold for twopence.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Two days after the release of the Parley version, Dickens sued on the basis of copyright infringement and won.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The publishers declared themselves bankrupt and Dickens was left to pay £700 in costs.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The small profits Dickens earned from *A Christmas Carol* further strained his relationship with his publishers, and he broke with them in favour of Bradbury and Evans, who had been printing his works to that point.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Dickens returned to the tale several times during his life to amend the phrasing and punctuation.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] While the public eagerly bought the later books, the reviewers were highly critical of the stories.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] By 1849 Dickens was engaged with *David Copperfield* and had neither the time nor the inclination to produce another Christmas book.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] He decided the best way to reach his audience with his "Carol philosophy" was by public readings.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] During Christmas 1853 he gave a reading in Birmingham Town Hall to the Industrial and Literary Institute.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] He insisted that tickets be reserved for working-class attendees at quarter-price and the performance was a great success.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Initially he donated the profits to good causes, although from 1858 he read the book for profit.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] He read the tale in an abbreviated version 127 times, until 1870 (the year of his death), including at his farewell performance.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] In the years following the book's publication, responses to the tale were published by W.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Swepstone (*Christmas Shadows*, 1850), Horatio Alger (*Job Warner's Christmas*, 1863), Louisa May Alcott (*A Christmas Dream, and How It Came True*, 1882), and others who followed Scrooge's life as a reformed man – or some who thought Dickens had got it wrong and needed to be corrected.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The novella was adapted for the stage almost immediately.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Three productions opened on 5 February 1844, one by Edward Stirling, *A Christmas Carol; or, Past, Present, and Future*, being sanctioned by Dickens and running for more than 40 nights.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] By the close of February 1844 eight rival *A Christmas Carol* theatrical productions were playing in London.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The story has been adapted for film and television more than any of Dickens's other works.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] In 1901 it was produced as *Scrooge, or, Marley's Ghost*, a silent black-and-white British film; it was one of the first known adaptations of a Dickens work on film, but it is now largely lost.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The story was adapted in 1923 for BBC radio.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] It has been adapted to other media, including opera, ballet, animation, stage musicals and a BBC mime production starring Marcel Marceau.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Davis considers the adaptations have become better remembered than the original.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Some of Dickens's scenes—such as visiting the miners and lighthouse keepers—have been forgotten by many, while other events often added—such as Scrooge visiting the Cratchits on Christmas Day—are now thought by many to be part of the original story.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Accordingly, Davis distinguishes between the original text and the "remembered version".
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The phrase "Merry Christmas" had been around for many years—the earliest known written use was in a letter in 1534—but Dickens's use of the phrase in *A Christmas Carol* popularised it among the Victorian public.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Humbug!" entered popular use in the English language as a retort to anything sentimental or overly festive; the name "Scrooge" became used as a designation for a miser and was added to the *Oxford English Dictionary* as such in 1982.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] In the early 19th century the celebration of Christmas was associated in Britain with the countryside and peasant revels, disconnected to the increasing urbanisation and industrialisation taking place.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Davis considers that in *A Christmas Carol*, Dickens showed that Christmas could be celebrated in towns and cities, despite increasing modernisation.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The modern observance of Christmas in English-speaking countries is largely the result of a Victorian-era revival of the holiday.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The Oxford Movement of the 1830s and 1840s had produced a resurgence of the traditional rituals and religious observances associated with Christmastide and, with *A Christmas Carol*, Dickens captured the zeitgeist while he reflected and reinforced his vision of Christmas.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Dickens advocated a humanitarian focus of the holiday, which influenced several aspects of Christmas that are still celebrated in Western culture, such as family gatherings, seasonal food and drink, dancing, games and a festive generosity of spirit.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The historian Ronald Hutton writes that Dickens "linked worship and feasting, within a context of social reconciliation".
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The writer James Joyce considered that Dickens took a childish approach with *A Christmas Carol*, producing a gap between the naïve optimism of the story and the realities of life at the time.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Ruth Glancy, the professor of English literature, states that the largest impact of *A Christmas Carol* was the influence felt by individual readers.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] In 1867 one American businessman was so moved by attending a reading that he closed his factory on Christmas Day and sent every employee a turkey, while in the early years of the 20th century Maud of Wales—the Queen of Norway—sent gifts to London's crippled children signed "With Tiny Tim's Love".
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Chesterton wrote "The beauty and blessing of the story ... lie in the great furnace of real happiness that glows through Scrooge and everything around him. ...
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] Analysing the changes made to adaptations over time, Davis sees changes to the focus of the story and its characters to reflect mainstream thinking of the period.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] While Dickens's Victorian audiences would have viewed the tale as a spiritual but secular parable, in the early 20th century it became a children's story, read by parents who remembered their parents reading it when they were younger.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] In the lead-up to and during the Great Depression, Davis suggests that while some saw the story as a "denunciation of capitalism, ...most read it as a way to escape oppressive economic realities".
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] The film versions of the 1930s were different in the UK and US.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] British-made films showed a traditional telling of the story, while US-made works showed Cratchit in a more central role, escaping the depression caused by European bankers and celebrating what Davis calls "the Christmas of the common man".
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] In the 1960s, Scrooge was sometimes portrayed as a Freudian figure wrestling with his past.
[src:apple-cider/a-christmas-carol] By the 1980s he was again set in a world of depression and economic uncertainty.
[src:apple-cider/a-very-gaga-thanksgiving] The program features guest appearances by Katie Couric, Art Smith, and Tony Bennett.
[src:apple-cider/a-very-gaga-thanksgiving] Gaga performed stripped down, acoustic versions of five songs from her second studio album, *Born This Way*, along with two Christmas songs and a duet with Bennett.
[src:apple-cider/a-very-gaga-thanksgiving] The special received critical acclaim and gave ABC its best ratings in four years for its respective time slot on Thanksgiving Day.
[src:apple-cider/a-very-gaga-thanksgiving] At the 2012 Dorian Awards, the special was nominated in the category of Best TV Musical Program of the Year but did not win the award.
[src:apple-cider/a-very-gaga-thanksgiving] A live EP of performances from the special, titled *A Very Gaga Holiday*, was made available for purchase from the iTunes Store.
[src:apple-cider/a-very-gaga-thanksgiving] The EP debuted on the *Billboard* 200 albums chart in the United States at number 52.
[src:apple-cider/a-very-gaga-thanksgiving] Katie Couric interviews Lady Gaga about her life and the inspiration behind her music at the Convent of the Sacred Heart in Manhattan, the school she attended as a child.
[src:apple-cider/a-very-gaga-thanksgiving] Gaga also performs nine songs to a small audience of friends and family, including "Born This Way", "Marry the Night", "You and I", "Hair" and "The Edge of Glory", as well as covers of Irving Berlin's holiday classic "White Christmas" and Nat King Cole's "Orange Colored Sky".
[src:apple-cider/a-very-gaga-thanksgiving] She also sings a duet with Tony Bennett of "The Lady Is a Tramp", originally from the 1937 musical comedy *Babes in Arms*, featuring the work of Gaga's trumpeter, Brian Newman.
[src:apple-cider/a-very-gaga-thanksgiving] Gaga sings "Bad Romance" onstage during a different scene.
[src:apple-cider/a-very-gaga-thanksgiving] American chef Art Smith makes a turkey dinner and waffles with Gaga.
[src:apple-cider/a-very-gaga-thanksgiving] In another scene, a small group of children gather around her as she blows glitter on them.
[src:apple-cider/a-very-gaga-thanksgiving] Gaga received dresses designed by Giorgio Armani, Stéphane Rolland, Azzedine Alaïa, and Martin Grant.
[src:apple-cider/a-very-gaga-thanksgiving] A promotional photo of Gaga was released that shows her "going full ice princess", which Erin Strecker of *Entertainment Weekly* presumed would be her primary apparel.
[src:apple-cider/a-very-gaga-thanksgiving] Smith commented, "It's important for people to see that this amazing woman [Gaga] has a family that supports her." A 30-second preview of the special premiered on November 20, 2011, on Lady Gaga's YouTube channel.
[src:apple-cider/a-very-gaga-thanksgiving] It revealed the appearances of Bennett, Couric and Smith.
[src:apple-cider/a-very-gaga-thanksgiving] The full TV special premiered on November 24, 2011, at 9:30 pm ET.
[src:apple-cider/a-very-gaga-thanksgiving] The program was met with acclaim from television critics.
[src:apple-cider/a-very-gaga-thanksgiving] Calling it engaging, Ken Tucker of *Entertainment Weekly* opined that *A Very Gaga Thanksgiving* was "disarmingly direct, sincere, and unpretentious".
[src:apple-cider/a-very-gaga-thanksgiving] Tucker praised Lady Gaga's performances in the television special, saying they were a "warm, low-key collection of solid performances of her hits and pop standards".
[src:apple-cider/a-very-gaga-thanksgiving] Dave Itzkoff of *The New York Times* said that while viewers might have thought they were viewing a "dream or a hallucination", they were watching "an actual holiday special".
[src:apple-cider/a-very-gaga-thanksgiving] On November 22, 2011, iTunes Store began selling an exclusive EP of the live performances from the special, which included "White Christmas", "Orange Colored Sky", "You and I", and "The Edge of Glory".
[src:apple-cider/a-very-gaga-thanksgiving] The EP was made available for purchase only.
[src:apple-cider/a-very-gaga-thanksgiving] Titled *A Very Gaga Holiday*, it entered the *Billboard* 200 chart at number 52, selling 22,000 copies, and number nine on the Top Holiday Albums chart.
[src:apple-cider/a-very-gaga-thanksgiving] The same week, the special also increased sales of Gaga's second studio album, *Born This Way*, which moved up the *Billboard* 200 chart from 72 to 21, with sales of 47,000 copies (up 416% from the previous week).
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Nicholas**" (often called "**The Night Before Christmas**" and "**'Twas the Night Before Christmas**", from its first line) is a poem, first published anonymously under the title "**Account of a Visit from St.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Authorship has been attributed to Clement Clarke Moore, who claimed authorship in 1837; but it has also been suggested that Henry Livingston Jr. wrote it.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] The poem has been called "arguably the best-known verses ever written by an American" and is largely responsible for some of the conceptions of Santa Claus from the mid-19th century to today.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] It has had a massive effect on the history of Christmas gift-giving.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Before the poem gained wide popularity, American ideas had varied considerably about Saint Nicholas and other Christmastide visitors.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Nicholas" was later set to music and has been recorded by several artists.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] On the night of Christmas Eve, a family is settling down to sleep, when the father is awakened by noises on their lawn.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Looking out the window, he sees Santa Claus, also known as Saint Nicholas, in a sleigh pulled by eight reindeer.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] After landing his sleigh on the roof, Santa bounds down the chimney.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] He carries a sack of toys, and the father watches his visitor deliver presents and fill the stockings hanging by the fireplace, and laughs to himself.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] They share a conspiratorial moment before Santa bounds up the chimney again.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] The authorship of *A Visit* is credited to Clement Clarke Moore who is said to have composed it on a snowy winter's day during a shopping trip on a sleigh.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] His inspiration for the character of Saint Nicholas was a local Dutch handyman as well as the historic Saint Nicholas.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Moore originated many of the features that are still associated with Santa Claus today while borrowing other aspects, such as the use of reindeer.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] The poem was first published anonymously in the Troy, New York *Sentinel* on December 23, 1823, having been sent there by a friend of Moore, and was reprinted frequently thereafter with no name attached.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] It was first attributed in print to Moore in 1837.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] In 1842, the noted poet and editor William Cullen Bryant credited Moore as the author when he included the piece in an anthology of American poetry he had compiled.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Moore himself acknowledged authorship when he included it in his own book of poems in 1844.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] By then, the original publisher and at least seven others had already acknowledged his authorship.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Moore had a reputation as an erudite professor and had not wished at first to be connected with the unscholarly verse.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] He included it in the anthology at the insistence of his children, for whom he had originally written the piece.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Moore's conception of Saint Nicholas was borrowed from his friend Washington Irving, but Moore portrayed his "jolly old elf" as arriving on Christmas Eve rather than Christmas Day.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] At the time that Moore wrote the poem, Christmas Day was overtaking New Year's Day as the preferred genteel family holiday of the season, but some Protestants viewed Christmas as the result of "Catholic ignorance and deception" and still had reservations.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] By having Saint Nicholas arrive the night before, Moore "deftly shifted the focus away from Christmas Day with its still-problematic religious associations".
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Moore's connection with the poem has been questioned by Professor Donald Foster, who used textual content analysis and external evidence to argue that Moore could not have been the author.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Foster believes that Major Henry Livingston Jr., a New Yorker with Dutch and Scottish roots, should be considered the chief candidate for authorship, a view long espoused by the Livingston family.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Livingston was distantly related to Moore's wife.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Foster's claim, however, has been countered by document dealer and historian Seth Kaller, who once owned one of Moore's original manuscripts of the poem.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] On January 20, 1829, Troy editor Orville L.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Holley alluded to the author of the Christmas poem, using terms that accurately described Moore as a native and current resident of New York City, and as "a gentleman of *more* merit as a scholar and a writer than many of more noisy pretensions".
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] In December 1833, a diary entry by Francis P.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Lee, a student at General Theological Seminary when Moore taught there, referred to a holiday figure of St.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Nicholas as being "robed in fur, and dressed according to the description of Prof.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Nicholas* appeared under Moore's name in *The New-York Book of Poetry*, edited by Charles Fenno Hoffman (New York: George Dearborn, 1837).
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Moore stated in a letter to the editor of the New York American (published on March 1, 1844) that he "gave the publisher" of *The New-York Book of Poetry* "several pieces, among which was the 'Visit from St.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Nicholas.'" Admitting that he wrote it "not for publication, but to amuse my children," Moore claimed the Christmas poem in this 1844 letter as his "literary property, however small the intrinsic value of that property may be".
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] 124–27 in Moore's volume of collected *Poems* (New York: Bartlett and Welford, 1844).
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Prior to 1844, the poem was included in two 1840 anthologies, attributed to "Clement C.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Moore" in *Selections from The American Poets*, edited by William Cullen Bryant (New York: Harper & Brothers, 1840), pp.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Moore" in the first volume of *The Poets of America*, edited by John Keese (New York: S.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] The New-York Historical Society has a later manuscript of the poem in Moore's handwriting, forwarded by T.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Moore along with a cover letter dated March 15, 1862, giving circumstances of the poem's original composition and transmission after a personal "interview" with Clement C.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Nicholas" appeared under Moore's name in the 1837 *New-York Book of Poetry*, newspaper printings of the poem often credited Moore as the author.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] For example, the poem is credited to "Professor Moore" in the December 25, 1837 *Pennsylvania Inquirer and Daily Courier*.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Although Moore did not authorize the earliest publication of the poem in the Troy *Sentinel*, he had close ties to Troy through the Protestant Episcopal Church that could explain how it got there.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Harriet Butler of Troy, New York (daughter of the Rev.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] David Butler) who allegedly showed the poem to *Sentinel* editor Orville L.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Holley, was a family friend of Moore's and possibly a distant relative.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] A letter to Moore from the publisher Norman Tuttle states, "I understand from Mr.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Daniel Sackett who was then a merchant in this city".
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] The reported involvement of two women, Harriet Butler and Sarah Sackett, as intermediaries is consistent with the 1862 account of the poem's earliest transmission in which T.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Moore describes two stages of copying, first "by a relative of Dr Moores in her Album" and second, "by a friend of hers, from Troy".
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Moore preferred to be known for his more scholarly works, but allowed the poem to be included in his anthology in 1844 at the request of his children.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] By that time, the original publisher and at least seven others had already acknowledged his authorship.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Livingston family lore gives credit to their forebear rather than Moore, but there is no proof that Livingston himself ever claimed authorship, nor has any record ever been found of any printing of the poem with Livingston's name attached to it, despite more than 40 years of searches.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] While textual analyses by English scholars have pointed to Livingston as the likelier author, subsequent tests using forensic linguistics techniques developed by computer scientists have come to the opposite conclusion.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] In his 2023 book *The Fight for "The Night": Resolving the Authorship Dispute over "The Night Before Christmas,"* retired litigator Tom A.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Jerman reported using Duquesne University computer scientist Patrick Juola's Java Graphical Authorship Attribution Program to compare the poem to the works of Moore and Livingston, with 16 of 17 tests pointing to Moore as the likelier author.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Advocates for Livingston's authorship argue that Moore "tried at first to disavow" the poem.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] They also posit that Moore falsely claimed to have translated a book.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Document dealer and historian Seth Kaller has challenged both claims.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Kaller examined the book in question, *A Complete Treatise on Merinos and Other Sheep*, as well as many letters signed by Moore, and found that the "signature" was not penned by Moore, and thus provides no evidence that Moore made any plagiaristic claim.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Kaller's findings were confirmed by autograph expert James Lowe, by Dr.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Joe Nickell, the author of *Pen, Ink & Evidence,* and by others.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] According to Kaller, Moore's name was likely written on the book by a New-York Historical Society cataloger to indicate that it had been a gift from Moore to the Society.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Livingston also wrote poetry primarily using an anapaestic metrical scheme, and it is claimed that some of the phraseology of "A Visit" is consistent with other poems by Livingston, and that Livingston's poetry is more optimistic than Moore's poetry published in his own name.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] But Stephen Nissenbaum argues in *Battle for Christmas* that the poem could have been a social satire of the Victorianization of Christmas.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Kaller claims that Foster cherry-picked only the poems that fit his thesis and that many of Moore's unpublished works have a tenor, phraseology, and meter similar to "A Visit".
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Moore had even written a letter titled "From Saint Nicholas" that may have predated 1823.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Foster also contends that Moore hated tobacco and would, therefore, never have depicted Saint Nicholas with a pipe.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] However, Kaller notes, the source of evidence for Moore's supposed disapproval of tobacco is *The Wine Drinker*, another poem by him.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] In actuality, that verse contradicts such a claim.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Moore's *The Wine Drinker* criticizes self-righteous, hypocritical advocates of temperance who secretly indulge in the substances which they publicly oppose, and supports the social use of tobacco in moderation and wine and opium, which was more acceptable then than now.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Foster also asserts that Livingston's mother was Dutch, which accounts for the references to the Dutch *Sinteklaes* tradition and the use of the Dutch names "Dunder and Blixem".
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Against this claim, it is suggested by Kaller that Moore – a friend of writer Washington Irving and member of the same literary society – may have acquired some of his knowledge of New York Dutch traditions from Irving.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Irving had written *A History of New York* in 1809 under the name of "Dietrich Knickerbocker".
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Jackson, a professor emeritus at the University of Auckland and a fellow at the Royal Society of New Zealand, authored a book in 2016, *Who Wrote "The Night Before Christmas"?: Analyzing the Clement Clarke Moore Vs.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Henry Livingston Question*, in which he evaluates the opposing arguments, using author-attribution techniques of modern computational stylistics to examine the long-standing controversy.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Employing a range of tests, including a statistical analysis of phonemes, Jackson contends that Livingston authored the classic poem.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] The latter 1963 stereo recording for Capitol Records became the most familiar of the poem's musical adaptations.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Christmas song-writing specialist Johnny Marks also composed a short version in 1952, titled "The Night Before Christmas Song", which has been recorded multiple times.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] It was also arranged for choir by Lee Kjelson and Margaret Shelley Vance.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] The poem was also set to music by British child composer Alma Deutscher (b.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] In 1953, Perry Como recorded a recitation of the poem for RCA Victor with background music arranged and conducted by Mitchell Ayres.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Louis Armstrong recited the poem in a March 1971 recording made only four months before his death.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] It was recorded at his home in Corona, Queens and released as 45 rpm by Continental Records.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Jo Stafford recorded a version of "'Twas The Night Before Christmas" as part of her 1955 album *Happy Holiday*.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] The first completely musical rendition, that used the text of the poem in its entirety without material additions or alterations, was the cantata "A Visit from St.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Dressel in 1992 and first performed by the Webster University Orchestra, SATB Soloists, and Chorus.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] More recent performances of the cantata have been performed by regional orchestras and choruses in Missouri, Illinois and Colorado.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] Four hand-written copies of the poem are known to exist and three are in museums, including the New-York Historical Society library.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] The fourth copy, written out and signed by Clement Clarke Moore as a gift to a friend in 1860, was sold by one private collector to another in December 2006.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] It was purchased for $280,000 by an unnamed "chief executive officer of a media company" who resides in New York City, according to Heritage Auctions which brokered the private sale.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] The poem is read or recited in numerous Christmas films, including *Prancer* (1989), *National Lampoon's Christmas Vacation* (1989), *The Santa Clause* (1994), *Reindeer Games* (2000), and *Falling for Christmas* (2016).
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] It also inspired two television specials called *'Twas the Night Before Christmas*, made in 1974 and 1977.
[src:apple-cider/a-visit-from-st-nicholas] '*Twas the Night Before Christmas* (2022) is a Hallmark Channel film about a town's annual Christmas Eve courtroom production debating the true authorship of the poem.
[src:apple-cider/a-winnie-the-pooh-thanksgiving] When Thanksgiving finally arrives, Winnie the Pooh and his friends bring food for the big dinner: honey, acorns, lemonade, biscuits, thistles and ice cream.
[src:apple-cider/a-winnie-the-pooh-thanksgiving] However, Rabbit informs them that the items they brought are not traditional to Thanksgiving.
[src:apple-cider/a-winnie-the-pooh-thanksgiving] He insists that a special traditional time of year should include special traditional items: turkey, cranberry sauce, special dishes and pumpkin pie.
[src:apple-cider/a-winnie-the-pooh-thanksgiving] Rabbit assigns Owl to wash the dishes, Gopher to make the pumpkin pie, Tigger and Eeyore to pick the cranberries, and most importantly, Pooh and Piglet to get the turkey (which Piglet believes to be a monstrous bird).
[src:apple-cider/a-winnie-the-pooh-thanksgiving] Tigger and Eeyore gather the cranberries, but fail to notice that there is a hole in the sack they used to gather the cranberries.
[src:apple-cider/a-winnie-the-pooh-thanksgiving] Meanwhile, Gopher blows up some pumpkins to make the pumpkin pie, creating a big mess in Rabbit's house.
[src:apple-cider/a-winnie-the-pooh-thanksgiving] When Tigger and Eeyore head back to gather more cranberries, they end falling in the turkey trap Pooh and Piglet had set up.
[src:apple-cider/a-winnie-the-pooh-thanksgiving] Thinking they have captured a real turkey, Pooh and Piglet bring the sack containing Tigger and Eeyore back to Rabbit.
[src:apple-cider/a-winnie-the-pooh-thanksgiving] Tigger and Eeyore manage to break out of the sack, shocking everyone.
[src:apple-cider/a-winnie-the-pooh-thanksgiving] In his excitement, Tigger flings the pumpkin pie in the air.
[src:apple-cider/a-winnie-the-pooh-thanksgiving] Chaos breaks out as Rabbit manages to catch the pie, only to get his face planted into the pie by Tigger after knocking him off the fallen table.
[src:apple-cider/a-winnie-the-pooh-thanksgiving] Owl loses control of the pile of plates he washed and thanksgiving decorations are destroyed.
[src:apple-cider/a-winnie-the-pooh-thanksgiving] Demoralized, Rabbit calls off the feast and sadly heads back home.
[src:apple-cider/a-winnie-the-pooh-thanksgiving] Everyone else disappointedly follows soon.
[src:apple-cider/a-winnie-the-pooh-thanksgiving] While sadly and contemplatively eating his honey, Pooh realizes that if they all shared the food they originally brought, everyone can have a great Thanksgiving.
[src:apple-cider/a-winnie-the-pooh-thanksgiving] Inspired and reinvigorated by this insight, Pooh rallies everyone and they surprise Rabbit with the Thanksgiving dinner they have set up.
[src:apple-cider/a-winnie-the-pooh-thanksgiving] Dazed and confused at first, Rabbit is warmed by the gesture.
[src:apple-cider/a-winnie-the-pooh-thanksgiving] They are all joined by Christopher Robin, who proposes a toast (with lemonade) to the best Thanksgiving celebration ever.
[src:apple-cider/a-winnie-the-pooh-thanksgiving] The special was originally aired Thanksgiving Day 1998 at 8 pm on ABC.
[src:apple-cider/a-winnie-the-pooh-thanksgiving] According to TVTango.com's ratings database, the initial airing brought in a 3.8 household Nielsen rating.
[src:apple-cider/a-winnie-the-pooh-thanksgiving] The special has not been released on home video by itself, with the exception of exclusive VHS tapes that were given to members of the Academy of Television Arts & Sciences for that year's show.
[src:apple-cider/a-winnie-the-pooh-thanksgiving] It was released to the general public as part of the VHS cassette *Winnie the Pooh: Seasons of Giving* with the narrator's lines were redubbed by Laurie Main, and the ending scene was shortened down, along with select episodes of *The New Adventures of Winnie the Pooh* in 1999.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Born in a one-room log cabin in Kentucky, Lincoln was raised on the frontier.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] He was self-educated and became a lawyer, Illinois state legislator, and U.S. representative.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Angered by the Kansas–Nebraska Act of 1854, which opened the territories to slavery, he became a leader of the new Republican Party.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] He reached a national audience in the 1858 Senate campaign debates against Stephen A.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln won the 1860 presidential election, becoming the first Republican president.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] His victory prompted a majority of the slave states to begin seceding and form the Confederate States.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] A month after Lincoln assumed the presidency, Confederate forces attacked Fort Sumter, starting the Civil War.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] As a moderate Republican, Lincoln had to navigate conflicting political opinions from contentious factions during the war effort.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] He closely supervised the Union's strategy and tactics, including the selection of generals and the implementation of a naval blockade of Southern ports.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] He suspended the writ of *habeas corpus* in April 1861, an action that Chief Justice Roger Taney found in *Ex parte Merryman* that only Congress could do, and he averted war with Britain by defusing the *Trent* Affair.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 1, 1863, he issued the Emancipation Proclamation, which declared the slaves in the states "in rebellion" to be free.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] On November 19, 1863, he delivered the Gettysburg Address, which became one of the most famous speeches in American history.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] He promoted the Thirteenth Amendment to the U.S.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Constitution, which, in 1865, abolished chattel slavery.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Following his re-election in 1864, he sought to heal the war-torn nation through Reconstruction.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] On April 14, 1865, five days after the Confederate surrender at Appomattox, Lincoln was fatally shot by John Wilkes Booth at Ford's Theatre in Washington, D.C., becoming the first U.S. president to be assassinated.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln is remembered as a martyr and a national hero for his wartime leadership and for his efforts to preserve the Union and abolish slavery.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] He is consistently ranked in both popular and scholarly polls as among the greatest presidents in American history.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Born in a one-room log cabin in Kentucky on February 12, 1809, Abraham Lincoln was raised on Sinking Spring Farm near Hodgenville, Kentucky.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] The captain was killed in a Native American raid in 1786.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] The family settled in Hardin County, Kentucky, in the early 1800s.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nancy is widely assumed to have been the daughter of Lucy Hanks.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas and Nancy married on June 12, 1806, and moved to Elizabethtown, Kentucky.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] They had three children: Sarah, Abraham, and Thomas Jr., who died as an infant.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's father bought multiple farms in Kentucky but could not get clear property titles to any, losing hundreds of acres in legal disputes.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1816, the family moved to Indiana, where land titles were more reliable.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] They settled on a forested plot in Little Pigeon Creek Community.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] In Kentucky and Indiana, Thomas worked as a farmer, cabinetmaker, and carpenter.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] At various times, he owned farms, livestock, and town lots, appraised estates, and served on county patrols.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas and Nancy were members of a Separate Baptist Church, a pious evangelical group whose members largely opposed slavery.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Overcoming financial challenges, Thomas obtained clear title to 80 acres (32 ha) in Little Pigeon Creek Community in 1827.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] On October 5, 1818, Nancy died from milk sickness, leaving 11-year-old Sarah in charge of the household, which included her father, 9-year-old Abraham, and Nancy's 19-year-old orphan cousin, Dennis Hanks.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Thomas married Sarah Bush Johnston, a widow with three children of her own, on December 2, 1819.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Abraham became close to his stepmother and called her "Mama".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 20, 1828, Lincoln's sister died in childbirth, devastating him.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] His formal schooling was from itinerant teachers.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] It included two short stints in Kentucky, where he learned to read, but probably not to write.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] After moving to Indiana at age seven, he attended school only sporadically, for a total of less than 12 months by age 15.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nevertheless, he was an avid reader and maintained a lifelong interest in learning.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Lincoln was a teenager his father relied heavily on him for farmwork and for supplementary income, hiring the boy out to area farmers and pocketing the money, as was the custom at the time.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] When he was somewhat older, Lincoln and some friends took a job carrying goods by flatboat to New Orleans, Louisiana, where the slave markets, according to the historian Michael Burlingame, "would leave an indelible impression on him....
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] In March 1830, fearing another milk-sickness outbreak, several members of the extended Lincoln family, including Abraham, moved west to Illinois and settled in Macon County.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Abraham became increasingly distant from Thomas, in part due to his father's lack of interest in education; he would later refuse to attend his father's deathbed or funeral in 1851.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Some historians, such as Michael Burlingame, identify Lincoln's first romantic interest as Ann Rutledge, a young woman also from Kentucky whom he met when he moved to New Salem, Illinois.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lewis Gannett disputes that the evidence supports a romantic relationship between the two.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] David Herbert Donald states that "How that friendship [between Lincoln and Rutledge] developed into a romance cannot be reconstructed from the record".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rutledge died on August 25, 1835, of typhoid fever.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln took her death very hard, sinking into a serious depression and contemplating suicide.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the early 1830s, Lincoln met Mary Owens from Kentucky.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Late in 1836, Lincoln agreed to marry Owens if she returned to New Salem.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Owens arrived that November and he courted her, but they both had second thoughts.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] On August 16, 1837, he wrote Owens a letter saying he would not blame her if she ended the relationship, and she declined to marry him.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1839, Lincoln met Mary Todd in Springfield, Illinois, and the following year they became engaged.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] She was a daughter of Robert Smith Todd, a wealthy lawyer and businessman in Lexington, Kentucky.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln initially broke off the engagement in early 1841, but the two were reconciled and married on November 4, 1842.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1844, the couple bought a house in Springfield near his law office.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] The marriage was turbulent; Mary was verbally abusive and at times physically violent towards her husband.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] The eldest, Robert Todd Lincoln, was born in 1843, and was the only child to live to maturity.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Edward Baker "Eddie" Lincoln, born in 1846, died February 1, 1850, probably of tuberculosis.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's third son, William Wallace "Willie" Lincoln, was born on December 21, 1850, and died of a fever at the White House on February 20, 1862.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] The youngest, Thomas "Tad" Lincoln, was born on April 4, 1853, and died of edema at age 18 on July 16, 1871.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln loved children, and the Lincolns were not considered to be strict with their own.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] The deaths of Eddie and Willie had profound effects on both parents.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln suffered from "melancholy", a condition now thought to be clinical depression.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1831, Lincoln's father moved the family to a new homestead in Coles County, Illinois, after which Abraham struck out on his own.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] He made his home in New Salem, Illinois, for six years.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] During 1831 and 1832, Lincoln worked at a general store in New Salem.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] He gained a reputation for strength and courage after winning a wrestling match with the leader of a group of ruffians known as the Clary's Grove boys.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1832, he declared his candidacy for the Illinois House of Representatives, though he interrupted his campaign to serve as a captain in the Illinois Militia during the Black Hawk War.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] He was elected the captain of his militia company but did not see combat.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his political campaigning, Lincoln advocated for navigational improvements on the Sangamon River.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] He drew crowds as a raconteur, but he lacked name recognition, powerful friends, and money, and he lost the election.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Lincoln returned home from the war, he planned to become a blacksmith but instead purchased a New Salem general store in partnership with William Berry.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Because a license was required to sell customers alcoholic beverages, Berry obtained bartending licenses for Lincoln and himself, and in 1833 the Lincoln–Berry General Store became a tavern as well.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Burlingame wrote that Berry was "an undisciplined, hard-drinking fellow", and Lincoln "was too soft-hearted to deny anyone credit".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Although the economy was booming, the business struggled and went into debt, prompting Lincoln to sell his share.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln served as New Salem's postmaster and later as county surveyor, but he continued his voracious reading and decided to become a lawyer.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rather than studying in the office of an established attorney, as was customary, Lincoln read law on his own, borrowing legal texts, including Blackstone's *Commentaries* and Chitty's *Pleadings*, from attorney John Todd Stuart.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] He later said of his legal education that he "studied with nobody." He was bestowed an honorary degree of Doctor of Laws by Columbia University in 1861.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] In Lincoln's second state house campaign in 1834, as a supporter of Whig Party leader Henry Clay, he finished second among thirteen candidates running for four places.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln echoed Clay's support for the American Colonization Society, which advocated abolition in conjunction with settling freed slaves in Liberia.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Whigs also favored economic modernization in banking, tariffs to fund internal improvements such as railroads, and urbanization.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln served four terms in the Illinois House of Representatives for Sangamon County.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] In this role, he championed construction of the Illinois and Michigan Canal.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln voted to expand suffrage beyond White landowners to all White men.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] He supported the chartering of the Illinois State Bank, and also led a successful campaign for moving the state capital from Vandalia to Springfield.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] On January 27, 1838, Lincoln delivered an address at the Lyceum in Springfield, after the murder of the anti-slavery newspaper editor Elijah Parish Lovejoy.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] In this ostensibly non-partisan speech, Lincoln attacked Stephen A.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Douglas and the Democratic Party, who the Whigs argued were supporting "mobocracy".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] His speech also attacked anti-abolitionism and racial bigotry.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln was criticized in the press for a planned duel with James Shields, whom he had ridiculed in letters published under the name "Aunt Rebecca".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Although the duel did not take place, Burlingame noted that "the affair embarrassed Lincoln terribly".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1843, Lincoln sought the Whig nomination for Illinois's 7th district seat in the U.S.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Hardin was the winning candidate, though Lincoln convinced the party convention to limit Hardin to one term.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln not only gained the nomination in 1846, but also won the election.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] The only Whig in the Illinois delegation, he was assigned to the Committee on Post Office and Post Roads and the Committee on Expenditures in the War Department.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Giddings on a bill to abolish slavery in the District of Columbia, but dropped the bill when it failed to attract support from most other Whigs.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln spoke against the Mexican–American War (1846–1848), for which he said President James K.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Polk had "some strong motive ... to involve the two countries in a war, and trusting to escape scrutiny, by fixing the public gaze upon the exceeding brightness of military glory—that attractive rainbow, that rises in showers of blood".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] He supported the Wilmot Proviso, a failed 1846 proposal to ban slavery in any U.S. territory won from Mexico.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Polk insisted that Mexican soldiers had begun the war by "invading the territory of the State of Texas ... and shedding the blood of our citizens on our own soil".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his 1847 "spot resolutions", Lincoln rhetorically demanded that Polk tell Congress the exact "spot" where this occurred, but the Polk administration did not respond.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] His approach and rhetoric cost Lincoln political support in his district, and newspapers derisively nicknamed him "spotty Lincoln".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln had pledged in 1846 to serve only one term in the House.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] At the 1848 Whig National Convention, he initially supported Henry Clay and was among the leaders of the Illinois delegation backing Clay, voting for him on the early ballots.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] When it became clear that Clay could not secure the nomination, Lincoln joined other Whigs in shifting support to Zachary Taylor, who won the party's nomination and the presidency in 1848.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] After Taylor won, Lincoln hoped in vain to be appointed commissioner of the United States General Land Office.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] The administration offered to appoint him secretary of the Oregon Territory instead.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] This would have disrupted his legal and political career in Illinois, so he declined and resumed his law practice.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln was admitted to the Illinois bar on September 9, 1836.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] He moved to Springfield and began to practice law under John T.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] He partnered for several years with Stephen T.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Logan and, in 1844, began his practice with William Herndon.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his Springfield practice, according to Donald, Lincoln handled "virtually every kind of business that could come before a prairie lawyer".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] He dealt with many transportation cases in the midst of the nation's western expansion, particularly river barge conflicts under the new railroad bridges.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1849 he received a patent for a flotation device for the movement of riverboats in shallow water and Lincoln initially favored riverboat legal interests, but he represented whoever hired him.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] He represented a bridge company against a riverboat company in *Hurd v.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Rock Island Bridge Company*, a landmark case involving a canal boat that sank after hitting a bridge.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] His patent was never commercialized, but it made Lincoln the only president to hold a patent.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln appeared before the Illinois Supreme Court in 411 cases.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] From 1853 to 1860, one of his largest clients was the Illinois Central Railroad, which Lincoln successfully sued to recover his legal fees.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln represented William "Duff" Armstrong in his 1858 trial for the murder of James Preston Metzker.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] The case is famous for Lincoln's use of a fact established by judicial notice to challenge the credibility of an eyewitness.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] After a witness testified to seeing the crime in the moonlight, Lincoln produced a *Farmers' Almanac* showing the Moon was at a low angle, drastically reducing visibility.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] In an 1859 murder case, he defended "Peachy" Quinn Harrison, the grandson of Peter Cartwright, Lincoln's political opponent.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Harrison was charged with the murder of Greek Crafton who, according to Cartwright, said as he lay dying that he had "brought it upon myself" and that he forgave Harrison.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln angrily protested the judge's initial decision to exclude Cartwright's claim as hearsay.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln argued that the testimony involved a dying declaration and so was not subject to the hearsay rule.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Instead of holding Lincoln in contempt of court as expected, the judge, a Democrat, admitted the testimony into evidence, resulting in Harrison's acquittal.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Compromise of 1850 failed to alleviate tensions over slavery between the slave-holding South and the free North.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] As the slavery debate in the Nebraska and Kansas territories became particularly acrimonious, Illinois Senator Stephen A.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Douglas proposed popular sovereignty as a compromise; the measure would allow the electorate of each territory to decide the status of slavery.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] The legislation alarmed many Northerners, who sought to prevent the spread of slavery, but Douglas's Kansas–Nebraska Act narrowly passed Congress in May 1854.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's Peoria Speech of October 1854, in which he declared his opposition to slavery, was one of an estimated 175 speeches he delivered in the next six years on the topic of excluding slavery from the territories.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's attacks on the Kansas–Nebraska Act marked his return to political life.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Nationally, the Whigs were irreparably split by the Kansas–Nebraska Act and other ineffective efforts to compromise on the slavery issue.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Reflecting on the demise of his party, Lincoln wrote in 1855, "I think I am a whig; but others say there are no whigs, and that I am an abolitionist....
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] I now do no more than oppose the *extension* of slavery." The new Republican Party was formed as a northern party dedicated to anti-slavery, drawing from the anti-slavery wing of the Whig Party and combining Free Soil, Liberty, and anti-slavery Democratic Party members.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln resisted early Republican entreaties, fearing that the new party would become a platform for extreme abolitionists.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln held out hope for rejuvenating the Whigs, though he lamented his party's growing closeness with the nativist Know Nothing movement.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1854, Lincoln was elected to the Illinois legislature, but before the term began he declined to take his seat so that he would be eligible to run in the upcoming U.S.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] At that time, senators were elected by state legislatures.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] After leading in the first six rounds of voting, Lincoln was unable to obtain a majority.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln instructed his backers to vote for Lyman Trumbull, an anti-slavery Democrat who had received few votes in the earlier ballots.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln's decision to withdraw enabled his Whig supporters and Trumbull's anti-slavery Democrats to combine and defeat the mainstream Democratic candidate, Joel Aldrich Matteson.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Violent political confrontations in Kansas continued, and opposition to the Kansas–Nebraska Act remained strong throughout the North.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] As the 1856 elections approached, Lincoln joined the Republicans and attended the Bloomington Convention, where the Illinois Republican Party was established.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] The convention platform endorsed Congress's right to regulate slavery in the territories and backed the admission of Kansas as a free state.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln gave the final speech of the convention, calling for the preservation of the Union.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] At the June 1856 Republican National Convention, Lincoln received support to run as vice president, but the party put forward a ticket of John C.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Frémont and William Dayton, which Lincoln supported throughout Illinois.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Democrats nominated James Buchanan and the Know Nothings nominated Millard Fillmore.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Buchanan prevailed, while Republican William Henry Bissell won election as Governor of Illinois, and Lincoln became a leading Republican in Illinois.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Dred Scott was a slave whose master took him from a slave state to a territory that was free as a result of the Missouri Compromise.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] After Scott was returned to the slave state, he petitioned a federal court for his freedom.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] His petition was denied in *Dred Scott v.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Taney wrote in his opinion that the Missouri Compromise was unconstitutional because it infringed on slave owners' property rights by prohibiting them from bringing their slaves into the territories.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] While many Democrats hoped that *Dred Scott* would end the dispute over slavery in the territories, the decision sparked further outrage in the North.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln denounced it as the product of a conspiracy of Democrats to support the Slave Power.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] He argued that the decision was at variance with the Declaration of Independence, which stated that "all men are created equal ... with certain unalienable rights", among them "life, liberty, and the pursuit of happiness".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] In 1858, Douglas was up for re-election in the U.S.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Senate, and Lincoln hoped to defeat him.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Many in the party felt that a former Whig should be nominated in 1858, and Lincoln's 1856 campaigning and support of Trumbull had earned him a favor.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] For the first time, Illinois Republicans held a convention to agree upon a Senate candidate, and Lincoln won the nomination with little opposition.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln accepted the nomination with great enthusiasm and zeal.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] The speech created a stark image of the danger of disunion.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] The Senate campaign featured seven debates between Lincoln and Douglas; they had an atmosphere akin to a prizefight and drew thousands.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln warned that the Slave Power was threatening the values of republicanism, and he accused Douglas of distorting Jefferson's premise that all men are created equal.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] In his Freeport Doctrine, Douglas argued that, despite the *Dred Scott* decision, which he claimed to support, local settlers, under popular sovereignty, should be free to choose whether to allow slavery in their territory.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] He accused Lincoln of having joined the abolitionists.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Though the Republican legislative candidates won more popular votes, the Democrats won more seats, and the legislature re-elected Douglas.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] However, Lincoln's articulation of the issues had given him a national political presence.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the aftermath of the 1858 election, newspapers frequently mentioned Lincoln as a potential Republican presidential candidate.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] While Lincoln was popular in the Midwest, he lacked support in the Northeast and was unsure whether to seek the office.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] In January 1860, Lincoln told a group of political allies that he would accept the presidential nomination if offered and, in the following months, William O.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Stoddard's *Central Illinois Gazette*, the *Chicago Press & Tribune*, and other local papers endorsed his candidacy.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] In February 1860, Henry Ward Beecher invited Lincoln to address his congregation at Plymouth Church in Brooklyn, New York.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln agreed, but the venue shifted to Cooper Union in Manhattan.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Many in the audience thought he appeared awkward and even ugly.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] But Lincoln demonstrated intellectual leadership, which brought him into contention for the presidency.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Journalist Noah Brooks reported, "No man ever before made such an impression on his first appeal to a New York audience".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Historian David Herbert Donald described the speech as "a superb political move for an unannounced presidential aspirant." In response to an inquiry about his ambitions, Lincoln said, "The taste *is* in my mouth a little".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] On May 9–10, 1860, the Illinois Republican State Convention was held in Decatur.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Exploiting his embellished frontier legend of clearing land and splitting fence rails, Lincoln's supporters promoted him as "The Rail Candidate".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] On May 18 at the Republican National Convention in Chicago, Lincoln won the nomination on the third ballot.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] A former Democrat, Hannibal Hamlin of Maine, was nominated for vice president to balance the ticket.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Throughout the 1850s, Lincoln had doubted the prospects of civil war, and his supporters rejected claims that his election would incite secession.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] When Douglas was selected as the candidate of the Northern Democrats, delegates from the Southern slave states elected incumbent Vice President John C.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] A group of former Whigs and Know Nothings formed the Constitutional Union Party and nominated John Bell of Tennessee.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln and Douglas competed for votes in the North, while Bell and Breckinridge found support primarily in the South.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] A nationwide militaristic Republican youth organization, the Wide Awakes, "turned it into one of the most excited elections in American history" and "triggered massive popular enthusiasm", according to the political historian Jon Grinspan.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] People of the Northern states knew the Southern states would vote against Lincoln and rallied supporters for him.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] As Douglas and the other candidates campaigned, Lincoln gave no speeches, relying on the enthusiasm of the Republican Party.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Republican speakers emphasized Lincoln's childhood poverty to demonstrate the power of "free labor", which allowed a common farm boy to work his way to the top by his own efforts.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Though he did not make public appearances, many sought to visit and write to Lincoln.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] In the runup to the election, he took an office in the Illinois state capitol to deal with the influx of attention.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] He also hired John George Nicolay as his personal secretary, who would remain in that role during the presidency.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] On November 6, 1860, Lincoln was elected as the first Republican president.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] His victory was entirely due to his support in the North and West.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] No ballots were cast for him in 10 of the 15 Southern slave states.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p01] Lincoln received 1,866,452 votes, or 39.8 percent of the total in a four-way race, carrying the free Northern states, as well as California and Oregon, and winning the electoral vote decisively.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] above the rotunda still under construction.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] following Lincoln's first inauguration portended imminent hostilities.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] After Lincoln's election, secessionists implemented plans to leave the Union before he took office in March 1861.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] On December 20, 1860, South Carolina adopted an ordinance of secession; by February 1, 1861, Florida, Mississippi, Alabama, Georgia, Louisiana, and Texas had followed.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Six of these states declared themselves to be a sovereign nation, the Confederate States of America, selecting Jefferson Davis as its provisional president.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] The upper South and border states (Delaware, Maryland, Virginia, North Carolina, Tennessee, Kentucky, Missouri, and Arkansas) initially rejected the secessionist appeal.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] President Buchanan and President-elect Lincoln refused to recognize the Confederacy, declaring secession illegal.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] On February 11, 1861, Lincoln gave a particularly emotional farewell address upon leaving Springfield for Washington.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and the Republicans rejected the proposed Crittenden Compromise as contrary to the party's platform of free-soil in the territories.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln said, "I will suffer death before I consent ... to any concession or compromise which looks like buying the privilege to take possession of this government to which we have a constitutional right".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln supported the Corwin Amendment to the U.S.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Constitution, which would have protected slavery in states where it already existed.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] The amendment passed Congress and was awaiting ratification by the required three-fourths of the states when Southern states began to secede.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] On March 4, 1861, in his first inaugural address, Lincoln said that, because he held "such a provision to now be implied constitutional law, I have no objection to its being made express, and irrevocable".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Due to secessionist plots, careful attention was paid to Lincoln's security and the train he took to Washington.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] The president-elect evaded suspected assassins in Baltimore.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] He traveled in disguise, wearing a soft felt hat instead of his customary stovepipe hat and draping an overcoat over his shoulders while hunching to conceal his height.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] On February 23, 1861, he arrived in Washington, D.C., which was placed under military guard.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Many in the opposition press criticized his secretive journey; opposition newspapers mocked Lincoln with caricatures showing him sneaking into the capital.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] The president ended his address with an appeal to the people of the South: "We are not enemies, but friends....
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] The mystic chords of memory, stretching from every battle-field, and patriot grave, to every living heart and hearthstone ... will yet swell the chorus of the Union, when again touched ... by the better angels of our nature".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Donald, the failure of the Peace Conference of 1861 to attract the attendance of seven of the Confederate states signaled that legislative compromise was not a practical expectation.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] In selecting his cabinet, Lincoln chose the men he found the most competent, even when they had been his opponents for the presidency.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln commented on his thought process, "We need the strongest men of the party in the Cabinet.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] We needed to hold our own people together.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] I had looked the party over and concluded that these were the very strongest men.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Then I had no right to deprive the country of their services." Doris Kearns Goodwin described the group in her 2005 biography of Lincoln as a "team of rivals".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln named his main political opponent, William H.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln made five appointments to the Supreme Court.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Noah Haynes Swayne, a prominent corporate lawyer from Ohio, replaced John McLean after the latter's death in April 1861.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Samuel Freeman Miller, who replaced Peter V.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Daniel, was an avowed abolitionist and received widespread support from Iowa politicians.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] David Davis was Lincoln's campaign manager in 1860 and had served as a judge in the Illinois court circuit where Lincoln practiced.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Democrat Stephen Johnson Field, a previous California Supreme Court justice, provided geographic and political balance.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Taney, Lincoln appointed his former secretary of the treasury, Salmon P.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Chase, to replace Taney as chief justice.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln believed Chase was an able jurist who would support Reconstruction legislation and that his appointment would unite the Republican Party.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early April 1861, Major Robert Anderson, commander of Fort Sumter in Charleston, South Carolina, advised that he was nearly out of food.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] After considerable deliberation, Lincoln decided to send provisions; according to Michael Burlingame, he "could not be sure that his decision would precipitate a war, though he had good reason to believe that it might".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] On April 12, 1861, Confederate forces fired on Union troops at Fort Sumter, starting the American Civil War.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] The April 12 and 13 attack on Fort Sumter rallied the Northern public to see military action against the South as necessary to defend the nation.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] On April 15, Lincoln called for 75,000 militiamen to recapture forts, protect Washington, and preserve the Union.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] This call forced states to choose whether to secede or to support the Union.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] North Carolina, Virginia, Tennessee, and Arkansas seceded.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] As the Northern states sent regiments south, on April 19 Baltimore mobs in control of the rail links attacked Union troops who were changing trains.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Local leaders' groups later burned critical rail bridges to the capital and the Army responded by arresting local Maryland officials.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln suspended the writ of *habeas corpus*, allowing arrests without formal charges.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] John Merryman, a Maryland officer arrested for hindering U.S. troop movements, successfully petitioned Supreme Court Chief Justice Taney to issue a writ of *habeas corpus*.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] In an opinion titled *Ex parte Merryman*, Taney, not ruling on behalf of the Supreme Court, wrote that the Constitution authorized only Congress and not the president to suspend habeas corpus.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] But Lincoln engaged in nonacquiescence and persisted with the policy of suspension in select areas.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Under various suspensions, 15,000 civilians were detained without trial; several, including the anti-war Democrat Clement L.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Vallandigham, were tried in military courts for "treasonable" actions, which was condemned as an attack on free speech.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln took executive control of the war and shaped the Union military strategy.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] He responded to the unprecedented political and military crisis as commander-in-chief by exercising unprecedented authority.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] He expanded his war powers, imposed a naval blockade on Confederate ports, disbursed funds before appropriation by Congress, suspended *habeas corpus*, and arrested and imprisoned thousands of suspected Confederate sympathizers.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln gained the support of Congress and the northern public for these actions.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also had to reinforce Union sympathies in the border slave states and keep the war from becoming an international conflict.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] It was clear from the outset that bipartisan support was essential to success, and that any compromise alienated factions in both political parties.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Copperheads (anti-war Democrats) criticized Lincoln for refusing to compromise on slavery; the Radical Republicans, who demanded harsh treatment against secession, criticized him for moving too slowly to abolish slavery.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] On August 6, 1861, Lincoln signed the Confiscation Act, which authorized judicial proceedings to confiscate and free slaves who were used to support the Confederates.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] The law had little practical effect, but it signaled political support for abolishing slavery.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's war strategy had two priorities: ensuring that Washington was well defended and conducting an aggressive war effort for a prompt, decisive victory.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Twice a week, Lincoln met with his cabinet.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Occasionally, Lincoln's wife, Mary, prevailed on him to take a carriage ride, concerned that he was working too hard.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Early in the war, Lincoln selected civilian generals from varied political and ethnic backgrounds "to secure their and their constituents' support for the war effort and ensure that the war became a national struggle".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] In January 1862, after complaints of inefficiency and profiteering in the War Department, Lincoln replaced Simon Cameron as secretary of war with Edwin Stanton.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stanton worked more often and more closely with Lincoln than did any other senior official.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Stanton's biographers Benjamin P.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Thomas and Harold Hyman, "Stanton and Lincoln virtually conducted the war together".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln saw the importance of Vicksburg for control of the Mississippi River valley and understood the necessity of defeating the enemy's army, rather than merely capturing territory.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] In directing the Union's war strategy, Lincoln valued the advice of Winfield Scott, even after his retirement as Commanding General of the United States Army.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] In 1861 Scott proposed the Anaconda Plan, which relied on port blockades and advancing down the Mississippi to subdue the South.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] In June 1862, Lincoln made an unannounced visit to West Point, where he spent five hours consulting with Scott regarding the handling of the war.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Internationally, Lincoln wanted to forestall foreign military aid to the Confederacy.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] He relied on his combative Secretary of State William Seward while working closely with Senate Foreign Relations Committee chairman Charles Sumner.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Navy illegally intercepted a British mail ship, the *RMS Trent*, on the high seas and seized two Confederate envoys.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Although the North celebrated the seizure, Britain protested vehemently, and the Trent Affair threatened war between the Americans and the British.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ended the crisis by releasing the two diplomats.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the Union rout at Bull Run and Winfield Scott's retirement, Lincoln appointed George B.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Early in the war, McClellan created defenses for Washington that were almost impregnable: 48 forts and batteries, with 480 guns manned by 7,200 artillerists.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] He spent months planning his Virginia Peninsula Campaign.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] McClellan's slow progress and excessive precautions frustrated Lincoln.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] McClellan, in turn, blamed the failure of the campaign on Lincoln's cautiousness in having reserved troops for the capital.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] In 1862, Lincoln removed McClellan as general-in-chief; he elevated Henry Halleck to the post and appointed John Pope as head of the new Army of Virginia.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] In the summer of 1862 Pope was soundly defeated at the Second Battle of Bull Run, forcing him to retreat to Washington.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Soon after, the Army of Virginia was disbanded.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Despite his dissatisfaction with McClellan's failure to reinforce Pope, Lincoln restored him to command of all forces around Washington, which included both the Army of the Potomac and the remains of the Army of Virginia.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lee's forces crossed the Potomac River into Maryland, leading to the Battle of Antietam.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] This battle, a Union victory, was among the bloodiest in American history.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] A crisis of command occurred for Lincoln when McClellan then resisted the president's demand that he pursue Lee's withdrawing army, while Don Carlos Buell likewise refused orders to move the Army of the Ohio against rebel forces in eastern Tennessee.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln replaced Buell with William Rosecrans and McClellan with Ambrose Burnside; according to Donald, this was a "shrewd" political move as they were non-partisan—unlike McClellan, a Democrat.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Against presidential advice, Burnside launched an offensive across the Rappahannock River and was defeated by Lee at Fredericksburg in December.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Facing low morale and discontent among the troops, Lincoln replaced Burnside with Joseph Hooker.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hooker endured heavy casualties at the Battle of Chancellorsville in May, then resigned in June and was replaced by George Meade.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Meade followed Lee north into Pennsylvania and defeated him in the Gettysburg campaign but then failed to effectively block Lee's orderly retreat to Virginia, despite Lincoln's demands.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant captured Vicksburg and gained control of the Mississippi River.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] In May 1863, Lincoln issued the Lieber Code, which governed wartime conduct of the Union Army, defining command responsibility for war crimes and crimes against humanity.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Two Union generals had issued emancipation orders in 1861 and 1862, but Lincoln overrode both: he found that the decision to emancipate was not within the generals' power, and that it might induce loyal border states to secede.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, in June 1862, Congress passed an act banning slavery in all federal territories, which Lincoln signed.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] In July, the Confiscation Act of 1862 was enacted, allowing the seizure of slaves from those disloyal to the United States.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] On July 22, 1862, Lincoln reviewed a draft of the Emancipation Proclamation with his cabinet.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Senator Willard Saulsbury Sr. criticized the proclamation, stating that it "would light their author to dishonor through all future generations".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] By contrast, Horace Greeley, editor of the *New-York Tribune*, in his public letter, "The Prayer of Twenty Millions", implored Lincoln to embrace emancipation.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Buttressed by news of the recent Union victory at Antietam, on September 22, 1862, Lincoln issued the preliminary Emancipation Proclamation, which proclaimed that, on January 1, 1863, all persons held as slaves within any state still in rebellion would be free.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] On January 1, 1863, he issued the final Emancipation Proclamation, freeing the slaves in the ten states not then under Union control, exempting areas under such control.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] With the abolition of slavery in the rebel states now a military objective, Union armies advancing south enabled thousands to escape bondage.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Proclamation was immediately denounced by Copperheads, who advocated restoring the union by allowing slavery.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] It was also seen as a betrayal of his promise to Southern Unionists not to tamper with slavery; Emerson Etheridge, then Clerk of the House of Representatives, joined an unsuccessful plot to give the Democrats and Southern Unionists control of the House.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a result of the Proclamation, enlisting freedmen became official policy.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] In a letter to Tennessee military governor Andrew Johnson, Lincoln wrote, "The bare sight of fifty thousand armed, and drilled black soldiers on the banks of the Mississippi would end the rebellion at once".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln gave the dedication for the Gettysburg battlefield cemetery on November 19, 1863.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] The address became the most quoted speech in American history.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Following Admiral David Farragut's capture of New Orleans in 1862, and after victories at Gettysburg and Vicksburg, Lincoln proclaimed a national Thanksgiving holiday, to be celebrated on the final Thursday of November 1863.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's victories at the Battle of Shiloh and in the Vicksburg campaign impressed Lincoln.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Responding to criticism of Grant after Shiloh, Lincoln said, "I can't spare this man.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] He fights." Following Meade's failure to capture Lee's army after Gettysburg and after Grant's success at Chattanooga, Lincoln promoted Grant to commander of all Union armies.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln reacted to Union losses by mobilizing support throughout the North.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Union forces targeted infrastructure—plantations, railroads, and bridges—to weaken the South's morale and fighting ability.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] While Lincoln sanctioned this approach, he emphasized the defeat of the Confederate armies over destruction for its own sake.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's bloody Overland Campaign turned into a strategic success for the Union despite a number of setbacks.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] But the campaign was the bloodiest in American history: approximately 55,000 casualties on the Union side (including 7,600 deaths), compared to about 33,000 on the Confederate (including 4,200 deaths).
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lee's losses, although lower in absolute numbers, were proportionately higher (over 50%) than Grant's (about 45%).
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early April, the Confederate government evacuated Richmond and Lincoln visited the conquered capital.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Amid the turmoil of military actions, on June 30, 1864, Lincoln signed into law the Yosemite Grant, which provided unprecedented federal protection for the area now known as Yosemite National Park.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and Secretary of the Treasury Salmon Chase faced a challenge in funding a wartime economy.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congress quickly approved Lincoln's request to assemble an army, even increasing his proposed 400,000 soldiers to 500,000, but both Congress and Chase initially resisted raising taxes.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the Union defeat at the First Battle of Bull Run, which collapsed the bond market, Congress passed the Revenue Act of 1861.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] This act imposed the first U.S. federal income tax, creating a flat tax of three percent on annual incomes above $800 ($28,700 in current dollars).
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] As the average urban worker made approximately $600 per year, many were not required to pay income taxes.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also signed increases to the Morrill Tariff, which had become law in the final months of Buchanan's tenure.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] These tariffs raised import duties considerably and were designed both to increase revenue and to help manufacturers offset the burden of new taxes.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Throughout the war, Congress debated whether to raise additional revenue primarily by increasing tariff rates, which most strongly affected rural areas, or by increasing income taxes, which most affected wealthier individuals; the latter view proved more popular.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] The revenue measures of 1861 proved inadequate for funding the war, forcing Congress to take further action.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] In February 1862, Congress passed the Legal Tender Act, which authorized the minting of $150 million in "greenbacks"—the first banknotes issued by the U.S. government since the end of the American Revolution.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Greenbacks were not backed by gold or silver, but rather by the government's promise to honor their value.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] By the end of the war, $450 million worth of greenbacks were in circulation.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congress also passed the Revenue Act of 1862, which established an excise tax affecting nearly every commodity, as well as the first national inheritance tax.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] It also added a progressive tax structure to the federal income tax.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] To collect these taxes, Congress created the Office of the Commissioner of Internal Revenue.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Despite the new revenue measures, funding the war remained challenging.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] The government continued to issue greenbacks and borrow large amounts of money, and the U.S. national debt grew from $65 million in 1860 to over $2 billion in 1866.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Revenue Act of 1864 represented a compromise between those who favored a more progressive tax structure and those who favored a flat tax.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] It established a five-percent tax on incomes above $600 and a ten-percent tax on incomes above $10,000, and it raised taxes on businesses.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] In early 1865, Congress reduced the threshold for ten-percent taxation to incomes above $5000.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] By the end of the war, the income tax constituted about one-fifth of the federal government's revenue, though it was intended as a temporary wartime measure.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln also took action against wartime fraud, signing into law the False Claims Act of 1863.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] This statute imposed penalties for false claims and made it possible for private citizens to file false-claim (*qui tam*) lawsuits on behalf of the U.S. government and share in the recovery.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hoping to stabilize the currency, Lincoln convinced Congress to pass the National Banking Act in 1863, established the Office of the Comptroller of the Currency to oversee "national banks," which were subject to federal, rather than state, regulation.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] In return for investing a third of their capital in federal bonds, national banks were authorized to issue federal banknotes.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] After Congress imposed a tax on private banknotes in March 1865, federal banknotes became the dominant form of paper currency.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Other economic policies passed under Lincoln included the 1862 Homestead Act, which made millions of acres of government-held land in the West available for purchase at low cost.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] The 1862 Morrill Land-Grant Colleges Act provided government grants for agricultural colleges in each state.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Pacific Railway Acts of 1862 and 1864 granted federal support for the construction of the United States' first transcontinental railroad, which was completed in 1869.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] At the start of the war, Russia was the lone great power to support the Union, while the other European powers had varying degrees of sympathy for the Confederacy.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to the historian Dean Mahin, Lincoln had "limited familiarity with diplomatic practices" but exerted "substantial influence on U.S. diplomacy" as the Union attempted to avoid war with Britain and France.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln appointed diplomats to try to persuade European nations not to recognize the Confederacy.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's policy succeeded: all foreign nations were officially neutral throughout the Civil War, with none recognizing the Confederacy.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Some European leaders looked for ways to exploit the inability of the U.S. to enforce the Monroe Doctrine opposing European colonial intervention in the Americas: Spain invaded the Dominican Republic in 1861, while France established a puppet regime in Mexico.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, many in Europe also hoped for a quick end to the war, both for humanitarian reasons and because of the economic disruption it caused.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] The European aristocracy was "absolutely gleeful in pronouncing the American debacle as proof that the entire experiment in popular government had failed", according to Don H.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Union diplomats initially had to explain that the United States was not committed to ending slavery, and instead they argued that secession was unconstitutional.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Confederate spokesmen were more successful by ignoring slavery and instead focusing on their struggle for independence, their commitment to free trade, and the essential role of cotton in the European economy.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Confederacy's hope that cotton exports would compel European interference did not come to fruition, as Britain found alternative sources and maintained economic ties with the Union.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Though the issuance of the Emancipation Proclamation in January 1863 did not immediately end the possibility of European intervention, it rallied European public opinion to the Union by adding abolition as a Union war goal.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Any chance of a European intervention in the war ended with the Union victories at Gettysburg and Vicksburg in July 1863, as European leaders came to believe that the Confederate cause was doomed.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Dole as commissioner of the Bureau of Indian Affairs and made "extensive use of Indian Service positions to reward political supporters", according to the historian Thomas Britten.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's policies largely focused on assimilation of Native Americans and diminishing tribal landholdings, consistent with those of his predecessors, but his direct involvement in Native American affairs was unclear.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] His administration faced difficulties guarding Western settlers, railroads, and telegraph lines from Native American attacks.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Tensions arose with the Dakota people due to American treaty violations, unfair trading, and government practices that led to starvation.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] In August 1862, the Dakota War broke out in Minnesota.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Hundreds of settlers were killed and 30,000 were displaced from their homes.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Some feared incorrectly that it might represent a Confederate conspiracy to start a war on the Northwestern frontier.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ordered thousands of paroled prisoners of war be sent to put down the uprising.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] When the Confederacy protested, Lincoln revoked the policy and none arrived in Minnesota.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln sent Pope as commander of the new Department of the Northwest.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Appointed as a state militia colonel, Henry Hastings Sibley eventually defeated the Dakota chief Little Crow at the Battle of Wood Lake.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] A war crimes trial led by Sibley sentenced 303 Dakota warriors to death; the legal scholar Carol Chomsky described the trial as "a study in military injustice" designed to "guarantee an unjust outcome".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln pardoned all but 39 of the condemned warriors, and, with one execution suspended, the remaining 38 were hanged in the largest mass execution in U.S. history.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Congressman Alexander Ramsey told Lincoln in 1864 that he would have received more re-election support in Minnesota had he executed all 303 warriors.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln responded, "I could not afford to hang men for votes." Lincoln called for reform of federal Indian policy but prioritized the war and Reconstruction.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Changes were made in response to the Sand Creek Massacre of November 1864, prioritizing peaceful administration of Native affairs and condemning those encroaching on Native territory, but not until after Lincoln's death.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln ran for re-election in 1864; the Democratic nominee was former general McClellan.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Republican Party selected Andrew Johnson, a War Democrat, as Lincoln's running mate.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] To broaden his coalition to include War Democrats as well as Republicans, Lincoln ran under the new label of the National Union Party.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Grant's bloody stalemates and Confederate victories such as the Battle of the Crater damaged Lincoln's re-election prospects, and many Republicans feared defeat.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln prepared a confidential memorandum pledging that, if he should lose the election, he would "co-operate with the President-elect, as to save the Union between the election and the inauguration; as he will have secured his election on such ground that he cannot possibly save it afterwards".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Victories at Atlanta in September and in the Shenandoah Valley in October turned public opinion, and Lincoln was re-elected with 55.1 percent of the popular vote as well as 212 electoral votes to McClellan's 21.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] As Grant continued to weaken Lee's forces, efforts to discuss peace began.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stephens, the Confederate vice president, and two other Confederate officials met with Lincoln and Seward at Hampton Roads.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln refused to negotiate with the Confederacy as a coequal, and the only agreement reached at the meeting concerned the exchange of prisoners.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's second inauguration took place on March 4, 1865; historian Mark Noll places his second inaugural address "among the small handful of semi-sacred texts by which Americans conceive their place in the world"; it is inscribed in the Lincoln Memorial.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] A month later, on April 9, Lee surrendered to Grant at Appomattox, signaling the end of the war.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] It triggered a series of subsequent surrenders across the South—in North Carolina, Alabama, and the trans-Mississippi Theater—and finally at sea with the surrender of the CSS *Shenandoah* in November 1865.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Reconstruction began before the war's end, as Lincoln and his associates considered the reintegration of the nation, and the fates of Confederate leaders and freed slaves.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] When a general asked Lincoln how the defeated Confederates were to be treated, Lincoln replied, "Let 'em up easy"; he focused not on blame for the war but on rebuilding.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Determined to reunite the nation and not alienate the South, Lincoln urged that speedy elections under generous terms be held.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] His Amnesty Proclamation of December 8, 1863, offered pardons to those who had not held a Confederate civil office and had not mistreated Union prisoners, if they signed an oath of allegiance.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln led the moderates in Reconstruction policy and was opposed by the Radicals, under Thaddeus Stevens, Charles Sumner and Benjamin Wade, who otherwise remained Lincoln's allies.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] As Southern states fell, they needed leaders while their administrations were being restored.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] In Tennessee and Arkansas, Lincoln appointed Andrew Johnson and Frederick Steele, respectively, as military governors.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] In Louisiana, Lincoln ordered Nathaniel P.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Banks to promote a plan that would reestablish statehood when 10 percent of the voters agreed, but only if the reconstructed states abolished slavery.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Democratic opponents accused Lincoln of using the plan to ensure his and the Republicans' political aspirations.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Radicals denounced his policy as too lenient and passed their own plan, the 1864 Wade–Davis Bill, but Lincoln pocket-vetoed it.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Radicals retaliated by refusing to seat elected representatives from Louisiana, Arkansas, and Tennessee.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] After implementing the Emancipation Proclamation, Lincoln increased pressure on Congress to outlaw slavery nationwide with a constitutional amendment.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] By December 1863 an amendment was brought to Congress.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] The Senate passed it on April 8, 1864, but the first vote in the House of Representatives fell short of the required two-thirds majority.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Passage became part of Lincoln's re-election platform, and after his re-election, the second attempt in the House passed on January 31, 1865.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] After ratification by three-fourths of the states in December 1865, it became the Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution, abolishing "slavery [and] involuntary servitude, except as a punishment for crime".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln announced a Reconstruction plan that involved short-term military administration, pending readmission under the control of southern Unionists.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] He also signed Senator Charles Sumner's Freedmen's Bureau bill that set up a temporary federal agency designed to meet the immediate needs of former slaves.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] The law opened land for a lease of three years with the ability for the freedmen to purchase title.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Eric Foner argues that "Lincoln did not see Reconstruction as an opportunity for a sweeping political and social revolution beyond emancipation.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] He had long made clear his opposition to the confiscation and redistribution of land." However, the Lincoln scholar Phillip S.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Paludan suggests that at the end of his life Lincoln was moving towards a more radical position, particularly with regards to freedmen's rights.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] John Wilkes Booth was a well-known actor and a Confederate spy from Maryland; although he never joined the Confederate army, he had contacts within the Confederate secret service.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] After attending Lincoln's last public address, on April 11, 1865, in which Lincoln stated his preference that the franchise be conferred on some Black men, specifically "on the very intelligent, and on those who serve our cause as soldiers", Booth plotted to assassinate the President.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] When Booth learned of the Lincolns' intent to attend a play with Grant, he planned to assassinate Lincoln and Grant at Ford's Theatre.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln and his wife attended the play *Our American Cousin* on the evening of April 14.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] At the last minute, Grant decided to go to New Jersey to visit his children instead.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] At 10:15 pm, Booth entered Lincoln's theater box, crept up from behind, and fired at the back of Lincoln's head, mortally wounding him.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's guest, Major Henry Rathbone, momentarily grappled with Booth, but Booth stabbed him and escaped.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] After being attended by Charles Leale and two other doctors, Lincoln was taken across the street to Petersen House.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] He remained in a coma for nine hours and died at 7:22 am on April 15.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's body was wrapped in a flag and placed in a coffin, which was loaded into a hearse and escorted to the White House by Union soldiers.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Johnson was sworn in as president later that day.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Two weeks later, Booth was located, shot, and killed at a farm in Virginia by Sergeant Boston Corbett.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] From April 19 to 20, Lincoln lay in state, first in the White House and then in the Capitol rotunda.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] The caskets containing Lincoln's body and the body of his third son Willie then traveled for two weeks on a funeral train following a circuitous route from Washington D.C. to Springfield, Illinois, stopping at several cities for memorials attended by hundreds of thousands.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Many others gathered along the tracks as the train passed with bands, bonfires, and hymn singing or in silent grief.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Historians emphasized the widespread shock and sorrow, but noted that some who had hated Lincoln celebrated his death.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Walt Whitman composed four elegies to Lincoln, including "When Lilacs Last in the Dooryard Bloom'd" and "O Captain!
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's body was buried at Oak Ridge Cemetery in Springfield and now lies within the Lincoln Tomb.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln redefined the political philosophy of republicanism in the United States.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Because the Declaration of Independence says that all men have an unalienable right to life, liberty and the pursuit of happiness, he called it the "sheet anchor" of republicanism, at a time when the Constitution was the focus of most political discourse.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] He presented the Declaration as establishing equality as a foundational principle for the United States, which had a significant impact on social and political movements in the U.S. into the 20th century.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a Whig activist, Lincoln was a spokesman for business interests, favoring high tariffs, banks, infrastructure improvements, and railroads, in opposition to Jacksonian democrats.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Nevertheless, Lincoln admired Andrew Jackson's steeliness and patriotism, and adopted the Jacksonian "belief in the common man".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] As a young man, Lincoln was a religious skeptic.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] However, he was deeply familiar with the Bible; throughout his public career, he often quoted scripture.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] His three most famous speeches—the House Divided Speech, the Gettysburg Address, and his second inaugural address—all contain such quotes.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] In the 1840s, Lincoln subscribed to the Doctrine of Necessity, a belief that the human mind was controlled by a higher power.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] After the death of his son Edward in 1850, Lincoln more frequently expressed a dependence on God.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] He never joined a church, although he and his wife frequently attended First Presbyterian Church in Springfield, Illinois, beginning in 1852.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] While president, Lincoln often attended services at the New York Avenue Presbyterian Church in Washington, D.C.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] The death of his son Willie in February 1862 may have caused him to look toward religion for solace.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's frequent use of religious imagery and language toward the end of his life may have reflected his own personal beliefs or might have been a device to reach his audiences, who were mostly evangelical Protestants.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Sources differ in how they describe his religious beliefs.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Stephen Mansfield describes "an atheist or religiously skeptical Lincoln" as "the prevailing view", although he argues that "there was a spiritual journey of some kind in Abraham Lincoln's life".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Richard Carwardine writes that "Many elements of the inner Lincoln, including his personal faith ... necessarily remain a puzzle".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln's last words were, as reported by his wife, "There is no place I so much desire to see as Jerusalem".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] According to Michael Burlingame, Lincoln was described as "awkward" and "gawky" as a youth.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] In adolescence he was tall and strong, participating in jumping, throwing, wrestling, and footraces, and demonstrating exceptional strength.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Burlingame notes that Lincoln's clothes "were typically rough and suited to the frontier", with a gap between his shoes, socks, and pants that often exposed six or more inches of his shin; "he cared little about fashion".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln was a slender six feet four inches, with a high-pitched voice.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] While he is usually portrayed bearded, he did not grow a beard until 1860 at the suggestion of 11-year-old Grace Bedell; he was the first U.S. president to do so.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Herndon described Lincoln's face as "long, narrow, sallow, and cadaverous", his cheeks as "leathery and saffron-colored".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Lincoln described himself as having a "dark complexion, with coarse black hair".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Although Lincoln's features were said to be "unpleasant to behold," Walt Whitman "wrote that Lincoln's face was 'so awful ugly it becomes beautiful.'" Lincoln's detractors also remarked on his appearance.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Among the illnesses that Lincoln is either documented or speculated to have suffered from are depression, smallpox, and malaria.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] He took blue mass pills, which contained mercury, to treat melancholy or hypochondriasis; this could have resulted in mercury poisoning.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] Several claims have been made that Lincoln's health was declining before his assassination, as photographs of Lincoln appear to show weight loss and facial changes.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p02] It has been proposed that he could have had a rare genetic disorder such as Marfan syndrome or multiple endocrine neoplasia type 2B.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p03] In surveys of U.S. scholars ranking presidents since 1948, the top three presidents are generally Lincoln, George Washington, and Franklin D.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p03] A 2004 study found that scholars in history and politics ranked Lincoln number one, while legal scholars placed him second after Washington.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p03] Kennedy, and Ronald Reagan were the top-ranked presidents in eight public opinion surveys by Gallup.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln's assassination made him a national martyr.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p03] He was viewed by abolitionists as a champion of human liberty.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p03] Many, though not all, in the South considered Lincoln to be a man of outstanding ability.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p03] In the New Deal era, liberals honored Lincoln as an advocate of the common man who they claimed would have supported the welfare state, and Lincoln became a favorite of liberal intellectuals across the world.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p03] The high point came in 1922 with the dedication of the Lincoln Memorial on the National Mall in Washington, D.C.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p03] The Black orator and former slave Frederick Douglass stated that in "his company, I was never reminded of my humble origin, or of my unpopular color", and Lincoln has long been known as the Great Emancipator.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p03] By the late 1960s, some Black intellectuals denied that Lincoln deserved that title.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lerone Bennett Jr. won wide attention when he called Lincoln a White supremacist in 1968.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p03] He noted that Lincoln used ethnic slurs and argued that Lincoln opposed social equality and proposed that freed slaves voluntarily move to another country.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p03] Defenders of Lincoln highlighted his condemnation of slavery and his contributions to its abolition, casting his delays and racist rhetoric as concessions to political necessity rather than reflections of his personal beliefs.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln has also been characterized as a folk hero and as "Honest Abe".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p03] David Herbert Donald opined in his 1996 biography that Lincoln was endowed with the personality trait of negative capability, attributed to extraordinary leaders who were "capable of being in uncertainties ... without any irritable reaching after fact and reason".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln has often been portrayed by Hollywood, almost always in a flattering light; the film historian Melvyn Stokes writes that "moviemakers have commonly used Lincoln primarily as a metaphor for ideas and values they approved".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln's portrait appears on two denominations of United States currency, the penny and the $5 bill.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p03] He appears on postage stamps across the world, including in Ghana, Honduras, China, Haiti, Nicaragua, Colombia, and Argentina.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p03] He has been memorialized in many town, city, and county names, including the capital of Nebraska.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p03] The United States Navy has named three vessels after Lincoln, including the *Nimitz*-class aircraft carrier USS *Abraham Lincoln* (CVN-72).
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p03] The Lincoln Memorial in Washington, D.C., is one of the most visited National Park Service sites in the country.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p03] Memorials in Springfield, Illinois, include the Abraham Lincoln Presidential Library and Museum, Lincoln's home, and his tomb.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p03] A carving of Lincoln appears with those of three other presidents on Mount Rushmore, which receives about 3 million visitors a year.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p03] A statue of Lincoln completed by Augustus Saint-Gaudens stands in Lincoln Park, Chicago, with recastings given as diplomatic gifts standing in Parliament Square, London, and Parque Lincoln, Mexico City.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p03] Several states commemorate "Presidents' Day" as "Washington–Lincoln Day".
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln has been extensively portrayed in media.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p03] Early works, such as *Abraham Lincoln's Clemency* (1910), attempted to mythologize him, emphasizing his mercifulness.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p03] Works from the Great Depression era, such as *Young Mr.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p03] Lincoln* (1939), embellished his early struggles and folksiness.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p03] The 1938 play *Abe Lincoln in Illinois* won a Pulitzer Prize and was adapted in film.
[src:apple-cider/abraham-lincoln-p03] After a marked decrease in film portrayals between 1941 and 1999, Daniel Day-Lewis won the Academy Award for Best Actor for his portrayal in *Lincoln*, a 2012 biographical film directed by Steven Spielberg.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Fresh liquid cider is extracted from the whole apple, including the apple core, trimmings from apples, and oddly sized or shaped "imperfect" apples, or apple culls.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Fresh cider is opaque due to fine apple particles in suspension and generally tangier than commercially cooked and filtered apple juice, but this depends somewhat on the variety of apples used.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Cider is sometimes pasteurized or exposed to UV light to kill bacteria and extend its shelf life, but traditional raw untreated cider is still common.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Some companies have begun adding preservatives and boiling cider, so that it can be shelf stable and stored without refrigeration.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] In either form, apple cider is seasonally produced in autumn.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] It is traditionally served on Halloween, Thanksgiving, Christmas, and New Year's Eve, sometimes heated and mulled.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Although the term "cider" is used for the fermented alcoholic drink in much of the world, it often refers to fresh "apple cider" in North America; *hard cider* is used there instead when referring to the alcoholic drink.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] In much of the U.S. and Canada, the fresh variety is often referred to as "apple cider" with "cider" alone referring to the alcoholic variety.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] While some states specify a difference between apple juice and cider, the distinction is not well established across the U.S.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] This still leaves unfiltered apple juice that is no longer raw in a gray area, presumably cider but not labeled as such.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] The addition of sweeteners or reconstitution from concentrate are left even grayer.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Canada recognizes unfiltered, unsweetened apple juice as cider, fresh or not.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Historically all cider was left in its natural state, raw and unprocessed.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] In time, airborne yeasts present on apple skins or cider making machinery would start fermentation in the finished cider.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Left on its own, alcohol would develop and forestall growth of harmful bacteria.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] When modern refrigeration emerged, cider and other fruit juices could be kept cold or frozen for long periods of time, slowing down fermentation.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Any interruption of the refrigeration, however, could allow bacterial contamination to grow.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Outbreaks of illness resulted in some state government regulations requiring any commercially produced cider to be treated either with heat or UV radiation.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] As a result, natural raw cider is a specialty seasonal beverage, produced on-site at orchards and small rural mills in apple growing areas and sold there, at farmers markets, and some juice bars.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Such traditional cider is typically made from a mixture of several different apples to give a balanced taste.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Frequently blends of heirloom varieties such as Jonathan and Winesap, once among the most sought-after cider apples for tangy flavor, are used.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Many US states now require that unpasteurized cider have a warning label on the bottle.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Even with refrigeration, raw cider will begin to become slightly carbonated within a few weeks, and eventually become hard cider as the fermentation process continues.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Some producers use this fermentation to make hard cider; others carry it further on to acetification and create artisanal apple cider vinegar.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Many commercially produced ciders are pasteurized or have artificial preservatives added which extends their shelf life; the most common method used is pasteurization, but UV irradiation is also employed.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Pasteurization, which partially cooks the juice, results in some change of the sweetness, body and flavor of the cider; UV radiation has less noticeable effects.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Cooking cider and adding chemical preservatives has allowed many ciders to be transported and sold without refrigeration.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Impetus for Federal level regulation began with outbreaks of *E. coli* O157:H7 from unpasteurized apple cider and other illnesses caused by contaminated fruit juices in the late 1990s.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Food and Drug Administration (FDA) made proposals in 1998; Canada began to explore regulation in 2000.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Canada, however, relies on a voluntary Code of Practice for manufacturers, voluntary labelling of juice/cider as "Unpasteurized", and an education campaign to inform consumers about the possible health risks associated with the consumption of unpasteurized juice products.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Modern cider making has come a long way from early forms of production that involved a man- or horse-powered crusher.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] These consisted of a stone or wood trough with a heavy circulating wheel to crush the fruit, and a large manual screw press to express the juice from the pulp.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Straw was commonly used to contain the pulp during pressing, later replaced by coarse cloth.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Company, of Cos Cob, CT, made the most popular "modern" rack and cloth press from the mid-1800s to the mid-1900s, when production shifted to OESCO in Massachusetts.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] As technology advanced, rotary drum "scratters" came into use.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Today, nearly all small pressing operations use electric-hydraulic equipment with press cloths and plastic racks in what is commonly called a "rack and cloth press", and electric hammermill "breakers".
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Depending on the varieties of apples and using the optimal extraction methods, it takes about one third of a bushel (10 liters) to make a gallon (3.78 liters) of cider.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Apples are washed, cut, and ground into a mash that has the consistency of coarse applesauce.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] The resulting juice is then stored in refrigerated tanks, pasteurized to kill bacteria and extend shelf life, and bottled and sold as apple cider.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] The juice may also be fermented to produce hard cider, which then may be further treated by exposure to acetobacter to produce apple cider vinegar, or distilled to produce apple brandy.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] The waste left after pressing, known as pomace, is sold for cattle feed.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Hot mulled cider, similar to "wassail", is a popular autumn and winter beverage.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Cider is heated to a temperature just below boiling, with cinnamon, orange peel, nutmeg, cloves, or other spices added.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Rosé apple cider can be obtained using red-fleshed applecrabs.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] "Cider doughnuts" traditionally used the yeast in raw cider as a leavener.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Today they are sometimes sold at cider mills and roadside stands, though there is no assurance natural cider is used.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Visiting apple orchards in the fall for cider, doughnuts, and self-picked apples is a large segment in agritourism.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Apple cider may be used to produce hard apple cider, apple wine, applejack, or apple brandy, among other possibilities.
[src:apple-cider/apple-cider] Apple cider is the official beverage of the U.S. state of New Hampshire.
